animal.description:
***We appreciate your interest in adopting a pug in need. Please respect our process and our time, as we are all volunteers with full time jobs.  An application starts the process.  We are not able to answer calls with questions about the foster pugs. ***

Hi there!  We are Pretzel and Twinkie, 10-year-old pug sisters who are BFFs (that's Best Friends Forever, for those not familiar with that term). When we came to APARN, we told the Fairy Pug Mother that all we wanted was to stay together, and she said that was a wish she could happily grant! We are together ALL the time. IF you think you can away with loving on just one of us, you are wrong! You’ll have two pugs in your lap faster than you can say “brachycephalic”!  We sleep together, lay around together, even go outside to go potty together! The only thing we need to do separately is eat, as we do not like to share food! We are very quiet pugs and really don’t require much other than some loving interaction.
 
Note: Twinkie is a three-legged pug; she was missing her front left leg when she came to APARN, so we don’t know what happened to her. While only having three legs does not slow her down, she did have a small Mast Cell Tumor removed from her right thigh two years ago.

***We encourage you to come to our adoption events to meet the pugs in person if you are interested in adoption. Again, please do not call regarding the adoptable pugs.  APARN is an all volunteer non-profit organization. We do not have a shelter. Our dogs are currently being fostered in private homes generally located throughout the greater Phoenix metro area.***
animal.name: Pretzel and Twinkie

animal.description:
Meet Deuce! Deuce is a 2 year old laid back staffie mix. His foster momma said he is just the coolest dog ever and he is going to make a family out there very very happy! He is fully grown at 56 lbs from his most recent vet visit. He has a big fenced in yard at his foster home that he loves to run in- we would ideally love for him to have a fenced in backyard at his furever home as well. He loves to hang out with other dogs and keeps himself entertained as well. He knows basic commands such as sit, stay, etc. He is great on leash or with a harness. He gets along great with other dogs that are medium size and larger. He cannot be placed in a home with a smaller dog. He would be fine in a home with children but is young with plenty of energy so he could knock little ones over. He is house and crate trained.

Deuce is UTD on all shots, neutered and microchipped. He is also heartworm negative. All of our dogs are current on flea, tick and heartworm prevention. 

Deuce is available for meet and greets locally. He can also be adopted out of state- a transport fee would apply in addition to his adoption fee. 
*All of our dogs come with 30 days of pet insurance when microchip membership is enrolled by adopters.

animal.description:
Hi guys my name is Red. Let me tell you a little bit about me. My bio may list me as a generic “hound” but I am anything but ordinary. I know my own mind and what I want more than anything is a family of my own. I’ve been waiting a long time (2 years) and once I find my special someone I want to be your one and only. This is what I bring to the table. I’m a bundle of fun and actually pretty larger than life with my goofy antics and oversize personality. I have all you need and more wrapped up in one gorgeous package. I am fun, active, loving and loyal. I will listen to your problems and never judge or offer unwelcome advice. What I will do is love you unconditionally, no matter what. As a matter of fact that is my specialty. 

So what does my favorite volunteer say about me: “I wish with all my heart Red would find a family of his own. He was left behind by my former neighbor and I got him to K4K a few years ago. I worry about him not getting enough time to run. He’s an active guy and would love an active family. I can see him curled up in someone’s home being spoiled rotten. It’s what he so deserves. He has had to compete for resources in the past and so does not really enjoy being in the company of other dogs. For a family that wants an only dog Red will be an awesome addition”.

So the take away here is my name is Red and I am in a word: Awesome. I’m a big ole hunk of love. I’m a pretty active 3 years old and I love walking, running around, giving kisses and hanging out with people (not dogs). I’m easy to get along with and a great listener. I know my own mind and a family of my own is my biggest wish. Please come meet me so we can get our life together started right away. For more info or to set up a meet and greet just email Karin 4 Kritters at karin4kritters@gmail.com or use the button at the top of this page to inquire about me. I'll be waiting patiently for you here at the rescue. Much love and kisses - Red...

***Note Red has tested positive for Heartworms. This is something we at the rescue will take responsibility for and will treat either before he is adopted or better case scenario in a foster to adopt situation. The rescue will pay for the treatment and Red’s new family can help him through the short recovery period. This consists mainly of short leash walking while minimizing over excitement. Red is a wonderful dog and is expected to live a normal life with a normal life expectancy after treatment and with a regular HW preventative after treatment. We recommend a preventative for every dog adopted from us or any other rescue or shelter.  If you have read this bio and would like to foster to adopt or outright adopt please contact us and we can explain the treatment and recovery in more detail or if you have decided he is not the right dog for you but you would like to contribute to his heartworm treatment please email the rescue at karin4kritters@gmail.com to find out how you can make a donation toward his treatment or to one of the other heartworm positive dogs at the rescue. Thank you.***
animal.name: Red

animal.description: Feebee does a happy dance when she sees one of her people and it will absolutely win you over. Feebee can be silly, too. She sometimes gets the 'zoomies' when she's around her caregivers and feeling especially happy. She gets equally excited to snuggle or to go for a walk on the trails. Feebee has a routine when meeting new people and she will need to continue this training in a home. Feebee thrives with structure, routine and a little patience. As long as she has that when she goes into a home, she will settle in just fine. Feebee is working on making dog friends but right now she is only comfortable walking next to them and not actually meeting them, so she would do best as the only dog in her new home. Feebee loves to learn and especially loves to show off the skills she has already learned. Feebee is an affectionate girl and a joy to be around, she would love to be your new best friend!

animal.description:
Poor Becky has had a tough time of it and REALLY, REALLY wants a family who will love her FUREVER!!!!!!!   
She came into rescue emaciated, scarred and heavily pregnant with 13 babies.Despite her "pit bull look", all we heard from her transporters was how wonderful, sweet and calm she was during her ten hour ride with four different families.  And she was just as loving as they come. Because she was so undernourished, six of the pups needed major surgery to reconstruct their bellies

When her babies were finally in their forever homes, it didn't take long for Becky to  find a foster-to-adopt home with a young man who truly loved her, and she him.  He would walk her daily, which she loved and they were very strongly bonded.  Sadly, when he lost his home, so did Becky.  After two years, she returned to rescue, but her heart was clearly broken.  It took weeks before we began to see the infamous, "happy dance"......but it DID return.  

Becky is housebroken, crate trained and has been cleared of her heartworm.  Her green eyes will make you smile everytime you see her.  If you are interested in adding this gal to your family FUREVER THIS TIME....Please go to https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1EHxp-7yawtDX2N50CEtUJECNh548bkLPFyJfJ3Zjg9w/edit and complete an application.

She is a very sweet and submissive girl, but can take a while to warm up to new people. Countess does well with other dogs and has a moderate energy level but is very playful. She would do best in a quiet home without young children, and with a dog savvy family who is willing to work with her and help her progress even more. We are estimating she is around 2 years old, and she weighs 25-30 lbs. 

Thank you for showing interest in our dogs, however due to the recent influx of applications and emails we ask that you avoid sending emails asking if: a listed dog is still available, if we received your application, or if we have additional photos (we always post whatever we have). Due to the current pandemic we have been receiving a huge influx of interest and emails and appreciate your help in lessening the workload for our volunteers. 

PLEASE NOTE: If you are interested in adopting a dog or puppy, please follow the steps below and submit an application. If you have questions you must reach out to us as we do not have the capacity to individually contact all applicants. During this time we are only accepting appointments at our Kingsburg facility, so please do not apply for a dog if you are not willing to drive to us.

Our dogs may be met by appointment locally in Kingsburg. Copy and paste the link below to submit a pre-screen application for the dog of interest, or find the link on our website www.pawsitiveconnections.org. animal.description:
UPDATE 12/20 ... Poor Moxy is recovering from ACL surgery and not available for visitors at this time. We will update this listing when she is feeling better.

***

UPDATE 3/20 ... From one of her favorite volunteer-pals: "We are kindred spirits in a way. I am usually not in a hurry and neither is she. She only gives me grief when I am rushing her back to her run."

.***

More than just soft fluff and a pretty face, Moxy is in search of a family that sees her for the smart, sweet girl she is, as well as the happy, confident dog she is capable of becoming. 

Moxy has lost her home twice over… so who can blame her for being a little insecure? Her first family moved to a place that didn’t allow pets. After a short stay at STAF, she was adopted by a nice, loving lady who was very generous with sweet words and snuggles. But Mox, with her chow guarding genes and boxer spunk, needs more. 

Without a strong, sure human to take the lead, Moxy became very protective of her owner both inside the house and out … which made her family more and more anxious … which only reinforced Moxy’s tendencies. A series of unfortunate events added to her inner turmoil: the death of her dog companion, the move to a new house with a smaller, unfenced yard, and the introduction of an invisible fence. (Not the right option for this already stressed dog.)

Despite her sporadic reactiveness to other dogs on walks, Moxy did great in doggy daycare. She was also making great strides with the in-house trainer … but unfortunately her owner could not get over her own anxiety. And since there are two ends to every leash, that meant Moxy could not move past it either. 

Those volunteers who have won Moxy's trust are granted the privilege of giving her long, leisurely belly rubs. (See video clip.) Yet the stress of shelter life is wearing on her, and she is desperately missing the comforts of home.

Moxy is eager to go on walks, but only allows those in her "inside circle" to leash/harness her. She is perfect in the car and so grateful to just sit and enjoy the view. She is house-trained and does well in her crate during the day … and also does fine when left out of the crate. She knows basic commands, including sit, down, and "watch me." She is around six years old and weighs in the low/mid 30s.

Moxie takes time to accept new people. With those humans she has come to know and trust, she will roll over to get belly rubs. But overzealous people who move in too fast may elicit a growl or a nip. She is not a social butterfly who enjoys having lots of people over, attending soccer games, or mingling at Starbucks ... Moxy is more of a hanging-at-home-with-the-family kind of girl. 

She has shared her homes happily with both cats and dogs, but the sometimes-unpredictable energy of younger kids and their friends would be too much for her at this time. 

Mox is in search of a confident, devoted human leader to help her overcome her fears and insecurities. She needs someone with prior dog experience who is versed in positive-based training. Another well-socialized dog may make Moxy’s transition to her new home easier. A fenced yard is a must--no exceptions. Sorry, but apartment dwellers and first-time dog owners need not apply. Her family-to-be will need to take it slow, making multiple visits to spend time with her at the shelter before taking the next step. If you fit the bill and think you might finally provide Miss Mox with her happily ever after, we can't wait to hear from you!

•  All of our animals are spayed/neutered and current on shots.
•  We do not do same-day adoptions; we ask that you return for a follow-up visit before taking an animal home.
•  You must be 21 years or older to adopt from STAF.
•  We require a 4-foot-tall physical fence for homes with children under the age of 11. We also may require a physical fence for specific dogs on a case-by-case basis, depending on each dog’s behavior and exercise needs.
•  Invisible fences: Due in part to increasing coyote activity/incidents in the area and the difficulty of predicting how a dog will respond to invisible fence training, we cannot adopt to homes with invisible fences.
•  We do request vet and personal references.
•  We can facilitate adoptions within a 75-mile radius of our Cincinnati-based shelter.

Please visit www.STAF.org for visiting hours, a downloadable application, and additional information.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 02/26/2019
Reason for being in rescue: Truman was part of a group of dogs seized from a home. CPR partnered with a local shelter to help these animals.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? None noted, he is a bit spicy but can be sweet, too.
Weight: 8.8 lbs
Height: in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? yes

What is my personality like? Truman has a personality the size of a Great Dane. When he steps out into his yard, he wants everyone to know it. To a new face, he wants to seem like a scary junk yard dog, but to his people he knows, he's simply a cuddly little mess. Truman is more comfortable with women than men, but a patient man can still win his heart. With new people he will bark and if pressed too hard, he'll bite. However, with treats and time, he will learn to trust anyone, and become a new snuggle buddy! He is very affectionate with the people he knows, but he is also very jealous.

Truman does not like having his ears messed with! If you pull on his ears, Truman will show teeth and let you know he is not happy.

Truman will chase away other dogs if they come too close while he is getting loved on. He always wants to be near his human friends, and will follow you everywhere. For a dog that tries to come across as scruffy, he is very affectionate. He is terrified on a leash, and freaks out as soon as he feels anything around his neck. He won't need professional grooming, but he will need someone very patient to bathe and brush him. He isn't one to really mess with toys yet, and playing with other dogs isn't something he does often, but he will get along with others in his area, as long as they aren't trying to steal the spotlight from him.

What kind of home would be best for me? The best home for Truman would be a quiet home with no children or other dogs. Someone who is patient, loving, and willing to understand where Truman came from. Knowing that he was in a hoarder situation, there are some behaviors he picked up to survive, and some of them will dissipate completely with time. Some, however, will always be a part of him, like a scar that won't heal. Truman will never be the dog that shows off his newest trick to your friends, but once he is familiar with them, he will be more than happy to con treats and belly rubs out of them.

How do I act when I first meet new people? At first, Truman will bark a lot, and if pressed too hard, he will bite. Feed him treats, and let him come to you, and soon you will have him eating out of your hand. He really does want to be loved, but his past makes that difficult for him.

Medical Information - Truman is up to date on all of his shots, Heart worm negative, and neutered. Unfortunately, he also has a long standing fracture in his jaw with a large piece of mandible missing. If a reduction were to be done, a major deformity would result causing a severe wry mouth worse than it is now. If repair was to be attempted, the success of this is speculative, and would need an oral surgeon to evaluate.

Other tips and tidbits: Truman's estimated birthday is 02/27/2016. Truman is a good boy, with a hard past and a lot of love to give for a long time to come. He needs a loving home that will help him take the difficult steps needed to learn how to be a normal lap dog.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

Meet Stewart! Stewart is a 5 year old Beagle. Stewart came to us emaciated, but he is now healthy and ready to be adopted! Stewart needs a home that will be patient and work with him on house training and socializing. Stewart is good with dogs his size and prefers female companions over males. He also needs a fenced yard where he cannot escape, and his "beagle nose" get him into trouble. He would not do well in a subdivision, apartment, or townhome. He is very vocal so a place with a little more land would be more suitable.
If you would like to make Stewart a part of the family, fill out an application at www.barktownrescue.org
STEWART'S ADOPTION FEE IS $170The shelter software system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at the dog's predominant breed or breed mix. We strongly encourage you to select your new pet by looking at each dog's individual personality and pet qualities rather than relying on a breed label that is only our best guess.

Our adoption fees vary from $150 and up. All of our dogs are up to date on vaccines, heart worm preventives, and flea/tick medication, and will be spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Portions of your adoption fee also help care for the sick and injured animals that we take in. Thank you for supporting us and considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
To quote Yogi Berra you might be thinking "dj vu all over again!" Yes, I am the same Babe ("Baby") you might remember from before, but I am a new girl in some ways. When I first came to CBHR a few months ago, I was rescued with Budde and we were very much dependent on each other. After some TLC from my fosters and a lot of socialization with another pair of bassets (Bo and Daisy), I am now my own woman. In fact, I am confidant and secure enough to live in a separate home. Just in case you're interested I am including our group photo while we were looking for attention (snacks actually) as part of my album.

I am healthy and friendly. Over the course of time my weight has caught up with me and my foster mom is helping me lose a few of those extra pounds. Otherwise I am in good shape for the shape I am inJ . Most of my days are spent resting and napping. I have found a corner in my fosters' yard that is my favorite place to be alone and just be. I have good manners and am content to be loved and fed. I am very good around people, cats, and other dogs. I guess you could say I just like to fit in. I have also become a bit of a "watch basset" and will let you know is a stranger is in the area.

You can most certainly still adopt Budde and me together, but I will be happy to be your only girl. I promise to just hang out with you and be a great, loving companion.

5/23/19

5 Black Labs/mixes in care pending medical and placement foster.

***Due to Covid, the "dog dry" situation in many pounds and a backlog of already approved adopters, we are only accepting applications for dogs with a name and bio on Petfinder.

Visit our website for more information on dog availability:  https://www.lelrr.org/

Please follow us on Facebook and Instagram LELRR501c3

We very much appreciate your interest in adopting a Labrador in need through LELRR. Please understand that this is a process, and it may take some time to both review and process your application, as well as to potentially adopt one of our Labs. One of the reasons that we ask for an application fee ($25) is that it takes the limited resources and time of our Trustees and volunteers to thoroughly review and process your application. (This fee is deducted from the adoption fee when you adopt.)

Please be patient; and be respectful of the volunteers and fosters that will work with you through this process. No one is paid, it is a labor of love, and we do our best to respond to applications and inquiries in a timely manner. 

That said, there is a reason that we ask applicants to specify the name of a dog in our application. With limited resources, we want to make sure that we are processing applications that will result in a successful adoption of one of our Labs in need. We cannot guarantee that you will be able to adopt the specific Lab that you are inquiring about. We always have more qualified applicants than we have Labradors available for adoption. 

Our job, and most especially the job of our fosters, is to place their dogs with the adopters that are the best fit for that specific Lab, and will offer them the best chance for success. If the Lab you originally applied for is adopted to someone else, please don't take it personally; and remember that we are always bringing in new Labs in need. One of them may very well be the perfect fit for your home. 

Your patience and understanding of our process is very much appreciated. Thank you!

That said, there is a reason that we ask applicants to specify the name of a dog in our application. With limited resources, we want to make sure that we are processing applications that will result in a successful adoption of one of our Labs in need. We cannot guarantee that you will be able to adopt the specific Lab that you are inquiring about. We always have more qualified applicants than we have Labradors available for adoption. 

Our job, and most especially the job of our fosters, is to place their dogs with the adopters that are the best fit for that specific Lab, and will offer them the best chance for success. If the Lab you originally applied for is adopted to someone else, please don't take it personally; and remember that we are always bringing in new Labs in need. One of them may very well be the perfect fit for your home. 

Your patience and understanding of our process is very much appreciated. Thank you!

Please note, RAGOM's adoption territory includes Minnesota, Iowa, North and South Dakota, and western Wisconsin within 75 miles of the MN border.   At this time, we do not adopt out of our territory.  

Hello, America! My name is Bentley, and I hailed from Turkey. Some kind-hearted people took me in from the streets and surrendered me to RAGOM.

I'm healthy at 10 years; I enjoy walking and outside time is my favorite! I love to just hang out in the grass or chase a few balls. I need a physical fence because I have a high prey drive and can't help running after those critters.

When I'm happy, which is most of the time, my whole body wags. With my natural zest for life, I may knock over the little ones inadvertently, plus I like to keep precious things to myself, so I should not live with children.

I love other dogs. The girls especially have me acting silly, dancing and spinning to get them to play with me! I probably shouldn't live with cats and small pets, though, due to my prey drive.

All in all, I'm a sweet, happy, goofy boy with lots of love and laughs to share. 

To learn more about Bentley, see his bio at:  https://ragom.org/dogs/bentley-19-096td

Placement Requirements:
Good With Dogs: Yes
Good With Cats: No
Good With Kids:  No due to resource guarding tendencies
Fence: Physical fence required
Age: Approx. 10

animal.description: 2-1/2 year old, handsome Taylor is in need of an adult-only home with someone who can give him some special help! He needs someone to teach Him how to be a treasured member of the family because it seems that his previous home may have kept him as an outside dog away from the comfort and companionship of his humans.  Taylor would love an active home where he can go on lots of hikes and walks and continue socializing with people. Taylor loves to play with his bones and toys. He would do best as the only pet in his forever home due to his prey drive and tendency to be selective about which dogs he wants to hang out with. Of course, he would also prefer to have the undivided attention, structure and training from his humans so they can help develop the  wonderful potential we see in him. He is doing well with his housebreaking and is learning manners that no one ever taught him like “sit,” “come” and how to walk nicely on a leash. He’s also learning how to properly greet new people as he gets very excited and wants to jump on them to say “hello.” Taylor has lots of energy and will need an adopter committed to providing  regular exercise, however, he settles down once he’s burned off the excess caffeine. Taylor is a very happy lab/pit bull mix at best guess who is somewhat independent, but also enjoys time spent with his humans and will make a loyal companion to whomever is lucky enough to adopt him.

PLEASE VISIT OUR WEBSITE AT WWW.PITRESCUE.ORG FOR INFORMATION ON OUR ORGANIZATION, ADOPTION POLICIES AND PROCESS, EDUCATIONAL INFORMATION, AND A FULL LIST OF OUR ADOPTABLE DOGS ALONG WITH PHOTOS AND FULL BIOS!!!
More pictures and info on this particular dog visit: https://www.pitrescue.org/truffle

Apply online: http://fs22.formsite.com/siouxempire/form1/index.html?1316620486706

*Adoption application must be filled out with home visit and references (personal and vet) required prior to any adoption. Filling out an application does not obligate you to adopt, but merely begins the process. SEPR DOES adopt out of state!

Adoption fees: All SEPR adoptions are $300 for adults and $400 for puppies 1 year and under.  This includes: adoption fee (spay/neuter, utd vaccinations, micro-chipping), microchip registration, Gentle Leader, and two tie downs for use in your home. 

SEPR requires all adopted dogs attend a training class with their adoptive family within 90 days of their adoption. If an adoptive family completes this training class, they will be refunded $100 of their adoption fee with proof of licensed certificate. SEPR even offers an obedience class called Train-A-Bull to alumni over 1 year of age on a seasonal basis.  These classes are currently free!

*All other pets in the residence must be spayed or neutered and all pets up to date on vaccinations.

*SEPR requires all applicants must be 21 years of age.

*SEPR dogs are adopted to be inside the home, “part of the family” dogs only.

*Families with children 5 years of age and under wanting to adopt puppies will be reviewed on a case by case basis. Raising a puppy properly takes a lot of time, and we understand that in families with small children, time can be a limited commodity.

animal.description:
Sawyer is a 2-year-old “Pocket Bully” born with a cleft lip, cleft palate, and spina bifida. He is currently eating and drinking safely on his own and we don’t believe his cleft lip/palate will require any surgical intervention. 

Sawyer will always need a little extra supervision to make sure he doesn’t eat anything dangerous for him, and will never be able to safely eat wet or goopy foods like canned food, peanut butter, yogurt, or any other liquids other than water. But otherwise he is expected to live a long, healthy life. 

The spina bifida causes Sawyer to be incontinent and to have some weakness in his back legs. He can walk and get around very well, but he will be in diapers for the rest of his life. He is a very happy, spunky pup and is friendly with humans and other dogs. He needs a committed home willing to give him the extra care he needs to thrive.

Sawyer has been neutered, is current on vaccinations, has tested negative for heartworm and is also micro chipped. 

We are committed to doing our part to control the spread of the COVID-19 virus. Until life goes back to normal, we will not be doing adoption events at PetSmart. Instead, we will be doing individual meetings by appointment and practicing social distancing at each meeting.

If you are interested in adopting, please complete our online adoption application at www.uaaf.org. For more information or to schedule an appointment, please email Jenn at jennc@mac.com or text at 801-554-9501.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.***Available For Adoption*** Local to DFW Metroplex Only***

Finn came into our program at around 10 weeks of age. His family had an accidental litter of puppies and they couldn't find a home that could meet his special needs.

Finn was born with a form of spina bifida called sacral agenesis. This means he was born without his sacrum. The sacral area is the control center for bowel and bladder control. Little Finn physically can't control his bowels or bladder so he has to wear a diaper.

Finn is pretty good about his diaper but sometimes he protests and removes the one that covers his rear end. He loves to run around naked!

Finn receives weekly chiropractic adjustments to help keep him as aligned as possible while he's still growing to help avoid any neurological issues in the future that a misalignment can cause. It also manages any pain he has from missing an important part of his back.

Given he is missing a pelvic stabilizing bone, his back end can be wobbly when he stands on his back legs. This does not slow him down ONE bit! He is FAST and can turn on a dime.

Lady Frankie came to us after she was attacked, suffering a severely injured ear that had been torn off and infested with maggots. This incredible girl doesn't let her past hold her back and she is ready to find her furever family.

- Lady Frankie loves cuddles...and plenty of them! Lady Frankie is quick to snuggle up in the bed or on the couch for some love from her humans!!
- She would do just about anything for peanut butter stuffed Kongs *SWOON*
- Enjoys older kids, especially when they sneak her the good treats!
- Likes going for walks, although she is still learning not to pull on leash
- Is currently learning the art of napping
- She rides like a champ in the car
- Is a pretty low maintenance girl who is fairly moderate energy. Doesn't need a ton of exercise to get all her energy out, but she's happy to tag along on adventures!
- Lady Frankie is a BIG KISSER! You'll never need to shower again!

Seeking:
-Home where she will be the only four-legged baby (no dogs, no cats)
-Family to love! Lady Frankie is a major love bug who enjoys showing her appreciation for her humans with her affectionate eyes and happy personality
-Not looking to go to the dog park/dog bar

Before emailing- please read:
- Yes, this dog is available for adoption
- The adoption fee for Lady Frankie is $256
- Apply at c2cnd.org
- The adoption fee covers their age appropriate shots, microchip, deworming, spay/neuter, and any other medical expenses while in our care.
- Local adopters only. Due to our thorough adoption process including home visits, we limit our adoptions to local families in the greater Charlotte area.
- If you have any additional questions, email us at dogs@c2cnd.org and we will respond as soon as possible!

animal.description:
Cute things come in small packages, 8-pound packages to be exact!

FOFINA is 12 years old, but you'd never know it to look at her.  She's lively, fit and really enjoys going for long walks.  I know what you're thinking, little 8-pound dogs are yappy!  Not this one, she keeps a lid on it, because she's mature and doesn't get excited about every little thing. 

Fofina's also an aficionado of House music, (old school, not the Johnny come lately stuff), which is to say, she likes "4 on the floor", which is to say, she would prefer not to be picked up.  It's embarrassing.

She's good-natured and a very well behaved little companion who would assimilate easily into an animal loving home.

***

OLDER DOGS ARE REALLY COOL...

...and I'll tell you why.  Because they're already broken-in!  Someone else has done all the heavy lifting. Taught 'em to take care of business outside, not to jump on company, some human language, how to be chill in the car, maybe even a few impressive tricks.

There's no better friend on Earth than a well-seasoned dog!

***

Animal Alliance is not a shelter where all the animals are housed in one location. Animal Alliance is a foster care network and animals are housed in many different locations. If you are interested in adopting a pet, please apply using the online application; applicants who call our phone line will hear a recorded voicemail with this identical message. We adopt many animals each week and meet prospective adopters at various locations so they can meet the animals they are interested in.

animal.description:
Bentley is a black and tan hound, 4 years old. About 50 lbs. Long legged. Friendly boy. He was very good in the car on the way to our rescue. Be sure to bring your dog to meet him - he seems to want to be the boss with other males. He recently met a tiny senior chihuahua and was sweet and kissy with him.
He's looking for a home that will help him to be active. He loves to go jogging and to play. He has a lot of energy and will need a doggie pal that can keep up with him!
He'd been an outside dog and may need to work on housetraining, though he does not soil where he eats and sleeps. Smart guy and the better teacher you are, the better student he is.
*Ready to go; he has all his shots, is chipped, and is neutered.
He was good friends with a large female dog at B&B - so we thought he was good with other big dogs....that has not been the case. Big potential companions come to meet him and he is fine for a little bit - social, playful - and then makes his move to see if he can be named Top #1 dog.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *

Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

Hazel came to Saving Grace in May 2019. She was abandoned on the side of the road in a crate. She has several wounds that we’re treating, as well as a misshapen head. animal.description:
She is not only beautiful but she's intelligent, too!  Nyx is learning many basic commands and special tricks!  She enjoys a fenced backyard so she can run and play!  She bonds quickly to people she knows she can trust.  Nyx is very loyal and will stick by her special person's side by following or sitting closely to that person.  She is a real sweetheart and very worth getting to know.

This girl will thrive in an adults only home without cats. Nyx is the perfect companion!  She is dog selective and will choose her canine friends.

Nyx is a 3 year old Italian Greyhound/Pit Bull mix who was surrendered by her owner who could no longer care for her.  She is heart worm free, microchipped, spayed and up to date on all vaccines.  She has a condition which causes seizures at times, but with proper diet, seizure medication and lots of loving care the seizures are controlled.  Nyx eats a limited ingredient diet due to allergies.

Nyx is currently in a foster home and being given lots of tender loving care. If you would like to meet her, please download our adoption application and email the completed form to adopt@bobbicares.org. Kindly keep in mind that our adoptions are local only (Long Island, Queens, Brooklyn, Manhattan).

This girl is so deserving of a permanent loving forever home.  If you would like to adopt her but simply can't at this time, please consider sponsoring her to defray the cost of her medical care.

animal.description:
Meet Jordi
 
My life goal is to have the non-beachy-est body pawsible. Why are ladies trying to lose weight to get into bikinis? It is so much delish to have a tummy, let me see that tootsie roll, muffin lump, chubby bump! When I was first rescued, I was extremely underweight and now that I have the oppawturnity to eat. I do. I could win the eating Chompion of the World.
 
My only grievance about my Foster Home is that they were feeding me 3 times a day and now that reduced it to only two. Hey, I want breakfast, brunch, lunch, linner, dinner, supper and bupper, if that’s a thing!
 
I am a blond bombshell and true to my girly roots, I love to steal, swipe, pilfer or borrow, yeah borrow….that sounds nicer…my Foster Mom’s shoes. Don’t worry, I don’t chew them up, I just like to relax with them and sniff that beautiful aroma alah Foster Mom Feet. Ahhhhhh!
 
I am not destructive and already know about house and crate training. I am after all a big girl now and not a puppy at just over 1 year old.  I am learning more manners. Plus at my Foster Mom’s house, I am learning to even take my own self out to potty with a tiny hobbit door made just for doggies and hobbits, I guess!
 
I am a work in progress, as all young German Shepherds need continual guidance and training to stay on track. But with my brains, I can learn anything. My Foster Home doesn’t have kids, but I am a gentle and sweet girl and would be good with older kids, but due to my health issue, a home with small kids would not be ideal.
 
What health issue? Glad you asked because I didn’t know how to bring it up in a normal convo. I do need a bit of help in the how do you say….powder room area? I have a broken tail and need to stay on a proper diet and be kept clean, so I do require a bit of assistance in the powder room. If all that sounds cool to you, apply for me today!
 
Basics:
Jordi- spayed female, 1 year old, German Shepherd, current on shots/microchipped, heartworm negative and on prevention, good with other dogs, good people, okay with cats, does have a broken tail so requires a special diet and some extra care, due to health issues no small children recommended.  See special diet below. ??
SPECIAL DIET FOR JORDI:  Cooked white rice mixed with RX clay available on Amazon.  Currently Venture brand turkey and sweet potato kibble but Costco Nature Domain turkey and sweet potato is okay. Also mix rice and clay mixture with a tablespoon of canned food for sensitive stomach and then mix the kibble with it. 

Link to Application:
http://www.gsdrescuectx.com/adoption-application.html

animal.description:
Adoption fee on this dog is $300.

		Zelda is a higher energy, spirited, happy, and sweet girl about 5 to 7 years old. She is not a dog for a first-time owner but would be a great addition for a family with German Shepherd or similar breed experience who understands the need for structure, leadership, and training. She should not go to a home with young children due to a strong herding instinct.

		Zelda gets along well with the other dogs in her foster home but you won't have squirrels or cats in your yard if she has her way. She can be a little dominate over a submissive pack mate so she would do best as an only dog or with a confident male. 

		She is missing some of her lower front teeth, its is unknown why, but has a clean bill f health from her dentist! Now she is ready to find someone with the dedication to direct her energy in a positive way.

This dog is a Level 3. Please be sure you understand what a dog of this Level requires. Go to our home page for an explanation of the Dog Rating Levels.

For more information and to see when this dog will be attending an Adoption Day, please see our Dogs page on our main website at www.gcgsr.org. 

We operate within a reasonable driving distance from the Greater Sacramento area, the 	Central Valley down to Merced, and Lake Tahoe. A reasonable driving distance is determined by where one of our volunteers is willing to drive within our areas of service. That means we don't adopt out of our area, to Southern California, or Out of State. 


Thank you for visiting!

animal.description:
Breed: Yorkie / Age: 2 year / Weight: 8 lbs.  /Sex: Male
HARRISON IS PARALYZED FROM HIS WAIST DOWN BUT STILL LIVING A HAPPY LIFE. 

Happy boy Harrison is eager to win your heart! Harrison was turned over to the police and was on his way to a kill facility if we didn't step up to save him. He has lower lumbar paralysis, meaning he can't use his rear legs. He is also bladder and bowel incontinent, so his bladder needs to be manually expressed 5 plus times a day. His bowel movement release on its own and you can manually speed the process most of the time. 

Harrison has no idea he is injured, he happily plays fetch and lives each day to the fullest. He is a wonderful companion for someone willing to keep up with his needs and in-home physical therapy. We are looking for that special person to see past his limitations and fall in love with his very deserving spirit. His previous people did get him the spinal surgery but didn't seem to do rehab. He’s been receiving Acupuncture, laser therapy, physical therapy and aqua therapy with a group of specialists who have trained us how to continue his therapy at home. He has also had I-Therm therapy which has helped and we are looking to get a machine for our rescue to continue his rehab and help our other special needs dogs. He shows signs of feeling from his paws and he has positive reactions to therapy. 

He sometimes uses his legs by showing strength. We are hopeful he will walk with continued home therapy. This absolutely adorable little guy is only a year old and 8 pounds. We are looking for a home for him who can keep up with his monthly grooming and heartworm prevention as well as daily health care and maintenance. 

His adoption fee is $200 to go towards his vetting (vaccines, spay/neuter, heartworm/Ehrlichia/Lyme test, fecal test, pre-op blood work, dental cleaning, microchip, and all his therapy/rehab). 

If you feel you can fulfill Harrison's needs he will drown you with kisses and his fantastic personality! If you are interested please fill out the adoption application For additional information regarding our adoption process, please check https://www.getalifepetrescue.com/galpr-info/adoptables/item/410-harrison.html

PLEASE READ HIS FULL BIO BEFORE APPLYING TO ADOPT! That means you need to READ!!! PLEASE BE AWARE***

WATCH VIDEO: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IwgJ0U3OEL4&feature=youtu.be

animal.description:
Rex is a 4-5 year old cattle dog. He came into our Rescue about a year ago as his owner went into a nursing home and was no longer able to care for him. Rex is the biggest snuggle bunny boy ever!
He loves scratches all over, especially butt scratches. Rex loves to lay on your lap and give you kisses forever! Rex is friendly with kids and people over the age of 14 and does great with other dogs as well. We are not sure about cats. Rex is super smart as well- when you call his name or talk to him, he will tilt his head to understand what is being said.  He is FULLY TRAINED, good on a leash, enjoys his walks and a great rider in the car. He's a medium energy dog that would make a fantastic pet. He can be a little bit leash reactive to other dogs at times, but it can easily be corrected with a bit of training! That being said, Rex is going to need someone that is going to continue with his training. He also needs a strong handler, and an experienced handler. Rex is not for first time dog owners.

animal.description: Meet JASPER!  When he first came into rescue, Jasper had to learn what it was all about to live in a house. He was terrified of everything & needed lots of time to figure out he was safe & what many things were, for example, the TV, stairs & even a dog bed. Jasper has come far but still needs patience with slow introductions to anything & anyone new to his life, therefore, he needs a very quiet, structured household with no children or cats, with an experience, patient dog handler who will understand & allow him time to adapt since new things & people still scare him.  He would make a great companion for a woman since he prefers women & is especially timid of men. He gets along well with other dogs that are his size with slow introduction & lives with 2 other dogs in his foster home. Words from his foster mom..."Jasper has found that dog beds are comfortable. He goes to the door to go out. Hides his 'treasures' in his crate (socks , toys, anything he likes that belongs to someone else but he does not damage them). Cuddles his stuffed toys. His favorite thing is his Kong. He walks well on leash & can be silly & dances!" This boy is guessed to be about 5 years old, weighs 58 lbs, up to date with vaccines, neuter, microchip, house trained, crated trained & the cleaning his pearly whites. Jasper had a rough start to life, has gone through heartworm treatment & is now Heartworm negative & given a good bill of health. He is maintained on Heartworm & flea prevention. If you think you could be Jasper's special person, please email Streethearts,animal.rescue@gmail.com & ask for an adoption application.

animal.description:
Date of birth: 9/20/2015

12/17/2020: Sela is a wonderful Pit Bull mix with the best smile!  She's a bundle of love -- she absolutely LOVES people and is extremely affectionate. She bonds very quickly. She is about 5 years old and she weighs 70 lbs.  

• Sela is fairly energetic and she loves to go for walks.  

• She’s a big strong girl! She’ll need a home with someone who has dog experience and can handle a strong dog on walks etc.

• She's very smart and has had some obedience training.  

• Sela has gone on weekend overnights with a volunteer and she's done very well in the home. She acts like she's lived in a home before. She's done well with being crated and only had a couple accidents when loose.  

• Sela is choosy with other dogs, so if you have a dog we'd ask you to bring your dog in to meet her so we could see if they could be buddies. She may do best as an only pet.  

• She has a prey drive and needs a home without cats.  

• She's kid friendly but she does get very excited when meeting people and needs some manners so that she learns not to jump up, so we think teenage kids would be best.

• Sela is not very vocal. She'd probably do okay in an apartment as long as her person provided plenty of exercise for her.  

• Sela was originally picked up by KCK Animal Services as a stray. She was there for several months so we transferred her to our shelter to find her a home. She has been spayed, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heart worms. Sela has so much love to give— she will be a loyal and adoring companion! 

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE: PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU. Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info.

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Dog Adoption Contact Info:
Email: christine@hsgkc.org
Phone: 913.596.1000 ext. 113
http://hsgkc.org

Hello, my name is Kris and I’m a volunteer for Karin 4 Kritters. Please meet my good friend Buddy. I write a lot of the Petfinder bios. I try my best to keep them light and entertaining while also giving the best glimpse of each dog’s unique personality. And that is what I did originally for Buddy. Of course I mentioned his extreme good looks and those adorable ears – so extra! I mentioned his eager enthusiasm for absolutely everything and his happy go lucky view of the world. But as I have gotten to know Buddy, and really fall for him, I realized that a cute bio with the cliché “would love to be your running partner” and the now obligatory bio standard “perfect companion to Netflix and chill” lines were just not enough to describe this amazing dog. Buddy is so much more than a few cute words and now tired catch phrases. And that is why I felt I had to do something different. I needed to give you, the reader, my experience with this wonderful dog. To say Buddy is beautiful is an understatement. If you could see him in person your jaw would drop. As beautiful as he is on the outside he is even more beautiful on the inside. 

So let’s start at the beginning. Buddy lived most of his life outside on a tether with his mom. Not fixed. One day the neighbor’s dog, also unfixed got into the yard and ran to Buddy’s mom. Buddy as you might imagine didn’t like that and a scuffle ensued. As a result both dogs were surrendered to K4K. Sadly Buddy’s mom was not surrendered so even though he had to leave his mother behind, finding himself at the rescue was actually his lucky break. It has given him the opportunity to find a loving forever home, inside, as a member of the family.  Here’s the thing I don’t understand, especially since I know Buddy so well. He has gotten no inquiries since we started the Petfinder profiles earlier this summer. The few people that come to the rescue never stop to look at him or ask about him. This is so surprising to me. Buddy has a deep capacity for empathy.  It’s a special ability that a select few dogs have as strongly as Buddy. He loves people and is so grateful for any attention shown to him. He is well mannered even in the face of great excitement – like the first few minutes after getting out of his kennel. He is eager to please and wants to learn. Someone that is willing to spend time with him training and laying the foundation for a strong lifelong bond would be ideal. Please don’t think for one minute that Buddy is all serious and no fun. Nothing could be further from the truth. He loves to have fun and act silly. That is what makes him such a great companion. He seems to know what you need and since he loves to please that is what he gives you. I find Buddy so lovable I can’t believe it isn’t obvious to everyone that sees him. I wish I could find the best way to let you know honestly and believably how wonderful this dog is. How he would be such a huge part of your life and how you would wonder after a few weeks with him how he was not always a part of your life while also seeming to have been a part of it forever. But then that is the magic of Buddy, which is best experienced in person.

If I have intrigued you even a little then you should email www.karin4kritters@gmail.com or inquire from this page. We will set up a time for you to meet this magical creature with the fantabulous ears for yourself. I can all but guarantee that if you meet Buddy you will love him just as much as I do. Thanks for reading about Buddy and his story of hope. We would love to hear from you...

***Note Buddy has tested positive for Heartworms. This is something we at the rescue will take responsibility for and will treat either before he is adopted or better case scenario in a foster to adopt situation. The rescue will pay for the treatment and Buddy’s new family can help him through the short recovery period. This consists mainly of short leash walking while minimizing over excitement. Buddy is a wonderful dog and is expected to live a normal life with a normal life expectancy after treatment and with a regular HW preventative after treatment. We recommend a preventative for every dog adopted from us or any other rescue or shelter.  If you have read this bio and would like to foster to adopt or outright adopt please contact us and we can explain the treatment and recovery in more detail or if you have decided he is not the right dog for you but you would like to contribute to his heartworm treatment please email the rescue at karin4kritters@gmail.com to find out how you can make a donation toward his treatment or to one of the other heartworm positive dogs at the rescue. Thank you.***

animal.description:
Sammy Hagar is losing his foster and needs a place to stay ASAP so he can decompress and regroup. 

Sammy is dog selective so a meet and greet is required. He is good with cats but no small kids (he is big and a bit clumsy). Sammy can be bossy so a home with bully breed experience is best.

Sammy has seperation anxiety when someone is home and he is put up (mostly verbal) that we are working to regulate through medication and exercise so he needs a home that will integrate him into their daily routine. Sammy cannot be kenneled but does well without it and is not generally destructive (save a few pillows that have fallen victim)..

Sammy came off of death row in St Louis County (he was Buckett there), for him to end up homeless again is devastating. He deserves a chance to live with a family again. Please offer to help. His life is in the balance.

FOSTER. SHARE. HELP!!!!

The adoption fee is $200. We do home visits as part of the adoption process for all of our dogs.  Due to that we only do adoptions within the Metro- St. Louis area.

animal.description:
Howdy there folks, my name is Pete! I am a 6 year old Treeing Walker Coonhound mix from the south! I am very friendly and quite an energetic guy who would love to find a home with a big yard and people who will love me forever! 

I would make for a great hiking partner, but regular neighborhood walks will do. With that being said, I am a favorite among the volunteers and staff when it comes to going on nice long walks, with a side of kisses. I am a bit more selective with my 4 legged dog friends but I do appreciate meeting calmer companions closer to my size. Cats and kids are nice and all but not for me.

I may be a "senior" but I am a young buck at heart and soul. I need some help continuing obedience and manners in the home, I do have separation anxiety so I would also need my people to work with me on improving my strong urge to be by your side 24/7. Due to my "hound howl", I would not do well with living in apartments or townhouses... don't wanna disturb your neighbors. Luckily, I will come with a training sponsorship from the sanctuary, so I will be set up for success!

If you would like to meet a southern gent, email us at adoption@sdsanctuary.com with any questions and to schedule an appointment to meet Peter!

Gerard is a huge love bug.  His ideal home would be as a single dog with not too many visitors, no young children, and no one who isn't capable of following the dog rules as he doesn't like to be confronted with another dog he doesn't know.  He is very good in the house, doesn't make a mess and really doesn't like to get dirty.  He responds well to routine, and is a super good boy on the walk.  He is kennel trained, and has no problem spending the night in his kennel, or perhaps during the day while you are out.  He does not have fear of storms or loud noises and is calm and non-reactive in his kennel.  We do not know how he would react to cats, but he can be aggressive with other male dogs if approached or charged. Some females he tolerates well if they do not get in his face or jump on him.  Gerard was neutered some time ago and is up to date on all shots.  He is ready to go upon an approved home for him.

animal.description:
Meet Sammy!

4 year old, Neutered Male, Australian Cattle Dog Mix, 45 lbs.

READ:  Must be local to Cleveland/Chattanooga/Knoxville TN area

Sammy is a quirky kind of boy.  He's best with strong female leaders in his household.  That includes having a female master (he absolutely will take advantage of anyone that shows him they are scared of him), and also a strong female dog that likes to play ROUGH like he does!  He is solid cattle dog when he plays -- teeth, chasing, body blocking, the whole 9 yards.  He needs a good fenced in yard and LOVES water.   ABSOLUTELY no children, cats, chickens, or any other small creature in Sammy's life.  He is crate trained and we believe he will be house trained.  Loves balls!

Sammy will not like a new person right away.  It will take several meetings on neutral turf before he accepts you.  Thusly, he will not tolerate strangers coming to your home or on your property, so you must be prepared to secure him if you have new people coming around.  

We hope that there is a perfect family for Sammy.  He waited in the animal shelter for 6 months, and now he has been in rescue over a year.  

Sammy is neutered, up to date on vaccines and flea/tick prevention, microchipped, heartworm negative, and is ready to leave for his new home right away!

He is currently in foster care with our rescue in Cleveland, TN,

For information or inquiries on how to adopt, please email us at pawsofvalor.ar@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Please read this entire paragraph.  We have dogs coming in all the time.  Because of COVID, there is a shortage of small, fluffy dogs.  We are struggling with our rescue partners to find these great adoptable dogs.  The shelter partners only have large dogs available as you can view for yourself as you check shelters and local rescues.

You will have to check our Petfinder website each week.  We hold applications open for two weeks as we match dogs and will not allow first come first serve.

We may not be the group for you as we don't allow apartments, condos, and out of area adoptions. We also require a fenced in yard and your patio or porch with a railing does not count.  The invisible fence is not allowed.  During the year we received only 17 dogs when we usually have 70 dogs throughout the year.  Each pet received 30-50 applications.  The last female dog we had in November 2020 received 80 applications.  We are telling you the statistics so understand that the past year was no usual dogs needing homes.  There are hardly any dogs in the shelters except large breeds.

Reputable breeders are not found in Penn Yan, NY, or the Southern Tier as the Puppy Millers live there. If you buy from a breeder ensure this breeder is of good standing and not breeding to make a living.  The parents should be in the home when you visit.  If the parents are not on-site, you are in a Millers' home.  Don't buy a puppy from a miller, as the mother dogs are held hostage for reproduction.  You don't want to be a part of the problem.   You should do the research and ask your vet for recommendations. The AKC has a list of breeders and this is where you should start your search if waiting a year for a shelter pet is not available to you.  Remember AKC has to follow the guidelines of the breed which in turn will result in a healthy dog, with no behavior problems.

animal.description:
Howdy my name is Maude. I'm kind of a pistol packing lil mama. A real firecracker...a spitfire...ahhh you get where I'm going with this. I'm a whole lot of fun packed into a chunky lil package. Sometimes I may come across as a little, ahhhhh, bossy. That's ok I'm really just a girl that knows her own mind. Being at Karin 4 Kritters and getting so much love and attention has helped me build my confidence. I'm getting better at walking on leash and I have found I'm a pretty good listener. That means I know how to take direction from the human walking me - that is if, big if, I don't come across a really interesting scent trail. Then you might have to have a treat handy to gain my attention. Treats are the bomb.com. I blame treats for my, ahem, plump figure. I'm a lot to love with a bit of junk in the trunk. Big trunk big personality that's what I always say and who doesn't want more of a good thing, more to love, more is better, you know it's true (wink).

Note from my favorite volunteer: “Maude is a hoot. She can be so silly and so loving all at the same time. She loves nothing more than to boss around her brother Claude, who is also available for adoption.  Maude is almost 2 and has been with our rescue for over a year. We love her dearly and want nothing more than to see her settled into her very own special home. She is such a chonkette and when she gets that junk in the trunk wiggling - it's the happiest sight you will see all day. I love this sweet, funny, amazing girl so much. It will be a happy day when I see her drive off on her way to her new home."

Come meet me like today. I'm ready to bring the fun and the funny, not to mention lots of love and slobbery kisses to your life. If you're ready to make your life immensely better you better come get me. Email the rescue at karin4kritters@gmail.com or hit the button on this page to set up an appointment to meet me. See you soon - love Maude...

PS: An additional note from Maude's biggest fan - Maude loves adventure, going to new places and riding in the car and running errands is an adventure to this sweet girl. She loves everyone and meeting new people is her favorite thing. She always calls shotgun and she makes an awesome wingman - girl - dog. You know what I mean...

animal.description:
Meet Shasta
Shasta is an absolutely gorgeous young dog, who could sure use a loving home. Shasta was owner surrendered on June 27, 2019. We think she’s a lovely girl with so much potential, and 19 months is way too long for her to spend in a shelter.
Shasta is an American Blue Heeler mix. She’s three years, eight monthsold and weighs 58 pounds. Shasta is very timid and doesn’t trust easily. However, once she trusts you she is so loyal, faithful and dedicated to her person, just hoping they’ll be good to her back. Shasta tries so hard to please. She learns quickly, follows directions easily and just laps up the attention of a good ear scratch or belly rub.
Shasta is very frustrated in the confines of her kennel and longs to be out and with people she likes. She is leashed trained and is easy to walk. Shasta is selective about what dogs she likes. She seems to be afraid of most of them and will go into a defensive posture to keep them away from her. Shasta may do best as an only dog, but we can test for potential adopters. Shasta’s behavior may change when out of the kennel and she’s able to bask in the steadying hand of love and a family who understands and protects her. 
If you’re looking for a wonderful, beautiful girl to make part of your family, come meet our Shasta. She has so much potential and lives to be someone’s best girl.
Shasta is spayed, micro-chipped and fully vetted. 
Call 706-865-4135 for information on additional health services provided as part of the adoption fee.  If interested in one of our puppies or dogs, please submit an application online or at the shelter. Applications can be submitted online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoption hours are Thurs and Fri 1-4 p.m., Sat 10 a.m.-4 p.m. and Sun 1-4 p.m. Closed Mondays, Tuesdays, and Wednesdays 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy. 75N, Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

animal.description:
Teddy is  a two and  a half  year old  German Shepherd who was purchased  from a breeder.  The owner bought him on a whim and quickly lost commitment as  Teddy grew  from puppyhood  to adolescence. Teddy  was  very smart  and  wanted  attention  but was  given none.  He needed  training but was given none. Instead  Teddy  was  then surrendered  to a high-kill shelter  and  was  rescued from the euthanasia list the week of July 4, 2018 by our rescue.    Teddy  came  to  us  with myriad of  issues.  His  behavior  left  much to be desired.  His  energy level was high. And most important,  Teddy  had  a health issue no one knew about.  In our care,  Teddy  was agitated, assertive  and losing weight by the pounds.  Through  a  grant  from the Petfinder Foundation we  were  able  to diagnosis and treat  Teddy's ailment.  Teddy  was  diagnosis-ed  with Exocrine Pancreatic Insufficiency known as EPI.  This is a condition in which the pancreas fails  to produce enough digestive enzymes which leads  to weight loss, diarrhea and makes the dog  feel overall lousy.  This  is  a  condition that  is  easily  treated  with a dose by weight of  enzymes.  Teddy  has  been  on enzymes  for  a year and has gained weight, developed  a personality in which  he listens and has learned some commands.  He  is less  irritable  and has become more social with other animals.   
The story of Teddy  is  a tough one because it exemplifies poor  breeding and poor ownership.  The story of  Teddy  is  why our  shelters  are filled daily with dogs people  have thrown away.  I will  be  honest with you  Teddy  was  a first for our rescue and he  was a major commitment  but  we refused  to give up.  Today Teddy  runs  and plays  like a normal dog.  You  can see it in his eyes  he is ready to please someone and fulfill  someone's life. If  you are interested in Teddy please know  that  his  enzymes most likely will  be a lifelong commitment as well as  a financial commitment.  Teddy  is  ready...finally!!!  We  are  willing to provide transitional training upon adoption. His adoption fee is $200 
Please email haltrescue@gmail.com or visit www.haltrescue.org for an application to adopt.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.DOG LOCATION: Killaloe, ONTARIO. Valen is a beautiful boy. A gentle soul and a dog who truly needed rescuing. We are here for Valen and now we're looking for his forever champion. Someone who is willing to get to know this sweet dog on his time, letting Valen decide how fast the relationship progresses.

You see, Valen came to us afraid of humans; terrified really. Too scared to eat when we're around, shutting even the softest noise or smallest movement, so terrified of human touch that he would urinate as soon as he felt our touch. He'd never lived in a house, known a soft bed, abundant food, clean water.

He rehabilitation has been painstakingly slow, requiring hours of patience. But the reward has been great. Just to see any bit of acceptance, maybe even happiness, from Valen is enough to make your heart soar! We're seeing glimpses of a dog who is now recognizing joy and good things in life.

Valen is now searching for his forever champion. That person or family who is willing and able to give him the best life he can have. Who lives in the country, has a fully fenced yard with a fence at least 6 feet tall, who has another dog and who is quiet and gentle. Someone willing to help Valen continue to learn about the big, scary world, but who is also willing to meet him where he is and accept him for who he is. Valen loves to go for walks but only the nature kind as sidewalks and streets are just too intimidating for him right now.

If you would like to be loved by this great dog, please email us to begin the conversation. Please note we require everyone to complete an adoption application prior to meeting any of our dogs. An adoption fee will apply. Valen is being fostered near Ottawa, Ontario
