animal.description:
Vinnie

 

Located in the Sidney NE area

Chihuahua and Jack Russell Terrier fusion is our best guess 

3-6 years old

Good with most other dogs and REALLY needs another playful small dog in the home

Cat friendliness unknown

Would do best in a home without kids, or only older kids that will allow him to come around on his own

NOT A FAN OF MEN (he will come around and allow a man to pet him but he doesn't want a man to pick him up or really push him beyond his comfort zone ) 

Crate trained and does know a couple commands

House trained

Fully vetted 

8-10lbs approx

 

Vinnie was found by a family a year ago and was unimpressed with humanity in general. He was covered with fleas and biting everyone who tried to get him. We were asked to help and we were shocked with how tiny he was when we arrived hahaha. Sybil threw a towel over his monkey butt and put him in her car and the rest is history hahah. Over the last year he has lived at A fosters homes with a lot of dogs and while he can be dominant when meeting new dogs, overall he corrects easily and then does fine going forward. He loves to play and he does play a little rough with other dogs so keep that in mind. He is a cuddly and sweet boy to women and would make an exceptional family member for a female only, or mostly, home. Vinnie has an amazing personality, he is such a clown and not only does he have epic bed head all the time, he SMILES, and is just hilarious! It's clear that Vinnie didn't have a good start and he LOVES his foster home, however he deserves a home where he gets way more attention and that is less busy as the coming and going makes him hyper alert. He is a good guard dog, despite his size, his bark is loud and unignorable, and he takes his job as protecting his person and home very seriously! 

If your looking for a charismatic, smiling, scruffy lil guy Vinnie is your man! 

If you would like to help Vinnie please contact us! 

 $200.00 Adoption Fee 

(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

To Contact Us

Message us through our website http://www.highplainspaw.org

Message the Facebook Page at https://www.facebook.com/HighPlainsPAW

Fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/adoption-application

Fill out our Foster Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/foster-application

Email us at highplainspaw@gmail.com

Call our voicemail at (402)957-1578

 

WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY ALL OUR DOGS ARE LOCATED IN FOSTER HOMES. This means there is no place for you to go in person to view our dogs. We ask that an application be filled out and we will go from there!

animal.description:
Meet Woodrow
Sometimes we just have to shake our heads and get it together for the dog’s sake. You see, this beautiful boy’s previous owner just walked away from him and never looked backed. Woodrow was found in an empty apartment after his owner moved out. He’d been without food, water, fresh air and no way out for who knows how long. Eventually, Woodrow was found by someone who works at the apartment complex. When Woodrow’s finder tried to keep him he was told no way by apartment management. Luckily, Woodrow’s hero asked us for help and we gladly took him in on June 8, 2019.  As of this date, he has spent over a year and a half in our shelter, which breaks our hearts.
Woodrow is a wonderful dog. He’s nothing but silly and sweet. He is currently 4 years old and weighs 65 lbs. Our best guess is that Woodrow is an American Pitbull terrier mix. He has stunningly beautiful markings and a sleek physique, and the cutest little bark. He loves every person he meets, but he does not like other dogs and cats so would be best as an only pet. Woodrow is showing himself to be a big love bug. He is an active dog and would do great with a family or person that makes him part of their activities. He walks well on a leash and is housetrained. We’re saddened that he could be so cruelly abandoned, but heartened that he is now safe and being loved on by shelter staff and volunteers.  He is definitely a favorite with staff and volunteers, and everyone is cheering for him to find his perfect home.
Woodrow has been fully vetted, neutered and microchipped. If you’re looking for a gentle- and fun - giant to make part of your family, come meet Woodrow. He’s that special kind of dog that will love to be your forever companion.
Call 706-865-4135 for information on additional health services provided as part of the adoption fee. If you can offer a safe indoor home to our puppy/dog, submit an application online https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Our shelter is currently closed to the general public as a result of the COVID-19 crisis. However, for approved adopters we are making appointments to meet and adopt your fur baby. 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy. 75N, Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

Name: Austin
Breed: German Shepherd mix
Age: 6 Years as of March 2020
Sex: Male 
Good with Kids: Yes, older preferred
Good with Cats: Yes
Good with Dogs: Yes

Austin is a stunning German Shepard Mix. He is fully vetted. He is good with older kids, other dogs, and cats. He was rescued from an abandoned house along with his siblings. He is feral and is about 70% rehabbed. He would do best in a home with other dogs. His perfect adopter would be one that not only understands his situation but is willing to put the time in to teach him his job, which is to be a good family dog. He is very responsive to teaching but needs personal attention on his journey to being at peace with being a family dog. He has been with a professional trainer and knows commands and does very well on the leash. He needs to be with a family who understands and embraces his shyness and can continue to work with him.

 Austin would do best with a couple of meet and greets with potential adopters. 

---
Peach County Animal Rescue is a rescue located in Fort Valley, GA. Our adoption fees range from $250-350+. Although our rescue dogs share a common bond with one another, no rescue story is the same (even when similar). Vetting costs vary depending on their health conditions. For us, it is never about the money. We are a non-profit. Thank you for your love and support! All of our dogs are fully vetted: up-to-date on annual shots, spayed/neutered and microchipped with a lifetime registration. We look forward to hearing from you!

If you would like to send in an application for this dog, please use the link below! https://peachcountyanimalrescueandrehabilitation.org/apply-now-2/

animal.description:
Bunny was found on a freezing January 2019 day, emaciated and missing a large portion of her face. Her skull and teeth were exposed, her injury was so severe we expected she would need to be euthanized. Her wounds were typical of those sustained in a dog fight, and we feared she’d been used as a bait dog. The vet had not seen anything quite like it and estimated she’d been in this condition for 3-4 days. She was truly a survivor!
 
Eventually her body was strong enough that we could begin the different surgeries she’d need to heal her face and ear canal, as well has her broken hip. Her severed ear canal was removed and sealed off, and while she cannot hear out of that side anymore, she still has that cute floppy ear! As for her broken hip, which caused her to limp and hop around, earning her the name “Bunny”, was corrected with a procedure called an FHO. We chose to go this route because it’s a faster healing process, and gives her back almost full range of motion. She’s also heart worm positive, so she’ll begin treatment for that soon.
 
Now that Bunny is feeling better and healed, she zooms around the house at full speed! She loves to steal shoes and take them to her bed. Thankfully she just collects them and doesn’t chew on them! She loves to run around the back yard, bark at the sky and lay in the shade under a tree. We don’t recommend a house with cats (to be on the safe side) because she has a pretty good prey drive. She literally ran headfirst into a fence chasing a lizard. LOL! The one time we know of where she had a cat encounter, she chased the cat but didn’t know what to do once she cornered it. The cat hissed at her and she ran away.
 
Given her rough life, it’s shocking how sweet she is with people. She loves to give kisses! And she’ll occasionally try to climb up into your lap! We’re currently working on her manners, teaching her not jump or climb on people. Having been malnourished for so long, she’s very food-motivated, so she’ll do anything for a treat! We also believe that for now, Bunny should be in a single dog home, allowing her time to continue to heal. 
 
Using clues about Bunny’s age, temperament and injuries, we have a pretty good idea of her history. Because she’s so loving and good with people, she was probably somebody’s beloved family pet. Then she was either lost or stolen and her new owners overbred her. During this time, she outlived her usefulness and was likely sacrificed as a bait dog. After she sustained her horrific injuries, she was cast out in the streets to die. Amazingly, Bunny’s will to live persevered and she was able to hang on long enough for us to find her and nurse her back to health. Her sacrifice did not go in vain and now she has a fabulous life and all that unpleasantness is behind her. Bunny is looking for her forever home where people can play with her, take her running and treat her like the princess she is!

animal.description:
Due to COVID 19, and the Illinois Shelter in Place order, we have experienced an overwhelming increase in the interest of animal adopting.  We have been inundated with more applications than we can process, as we are an all-volunteer agency.  

We do sincerely thank you for your interest in adoption.  At this time, we will only be reaching out to applicants who may be a potential match for one of our available animals.  

NOTE: WE ARE FOSTER BASED, AND ONLY FULLY APPROVED APPLICATIONS ARE SCHEDULED FOR A MEET AND GREET. 

Again, we are all volunteers, and do our best to acknowledge/respond to all applications and inquiries, in a timely manner. 

Please read the bio below - in it's entirety - before submitting an application.  

Thank you!

Hello, my name is a Pepper and I am a two and a half year old American Bulldog mix.  I am an incredibly loving dog that would be a joyful addition to a good home, but first I want to tell you about my history.  

I was taken into foster care because of terrible neglect.  I was skin and bones and never knew love, everything was survival to me.  No one ever taught me human rules.  That all changed though when a nice lady rescued me.  Since then, I have learned a lot and everyone is very happy with me and my progress. 
 I have even been to school to help me learn my manners.  I have learned, sit, come, stay and drop it. I am good on walks and excellent in the car. I am well behaved in public, but sometimes need to be reminded to calm down when I see other dogs or squirrels.

I wait until I am invited to my food and will just walk away to avoid a conflict if you decide to take it from me. I absolutely adore people. I am a super-snuggler and love human contact. I sometimes still get a little mouthy or too goofy with excitement, but I have learned to calm down if told to do so. I’m okay with children and other dogs, but I think a home without young children or other pets may be best for me. 

I’m okay with the vacuum cleaner. I don’t like it, so I just avoid it. It’s a fair compromise.  I’ve even learned to get over my fear of the dishwasher when it’s running. I need an active family or person that is calm and consistent with manners and rules in order to thrive. I am extremely athletic and would do well in agility courses, jogging with you or going on hikes. I need physical activity. I love to play and have a darling, funny personality. I love my toys and understand now, that they are to be shared and enjoyed not guarded.  I also love to binge watch TV on the couch for hours. 

I am smart.  I lean very quickly and want to please. I am a happy, sensitive soul.  Do I sound like a good match for you?  If interested please fill out an application at www.placingpawsrescue.org.  I promise, you won’t regret it. 

ADOPTION FEE: $350.00 The adoption fee includes all age appropriate vaccinations including rabies, HW test if age appropriate, de-worming, microchip, fecal, spay or neuter, Heartworm and flea and tick preventative.  ADOPTION PROCESS: PLEASE READ CAREFULLY The first step in the adoption process is to fill out an application online at www.placingpawsrescue.org. Once we review the applications, those applicants that are thought to be a good match will be contacted as quickly as possible. We ask that you please be patient with us as we are all volunteers. Then a telephone interview will take place, references checked and a home visit will be conducted. We will then arrange for you to meet the dog. We require that all family members, including current dogs meet the dog prior to adoption.  We put all of the known information in the animals description. If the animal is listed on the website, we are still accepting applications for that animal. We only remove the animal when the final adoption paperwork is signed. The best way to contact us is by email at placingpaws@yahoo.com. It is very difficult for the limited numbers of volunteers to return all calls. Thank you.

animal.description:
*8 year old lab mix*
From Forrest’s loving foster....

This boy is a gorgeous lab mix. He is very easy going in the way of daily routines, and he’s happy to hang out & lounge, or nap, or be active and play or go for a walk as you wish. 

Forrest can keep himself busy with a bone or ball. He is potty trained and is used to going out 4x a day for potty breaks. He is not destructive, and should be fine wandering free in a house. 

His quirks are that due to his past, he does not appreciate anyone touching from the back of his neck back to his rear area. So keeping the petting to his head is a must. Also once he is given a bone or ball, if it is within his reach, he
does not appreciate anyone coming near it. However we have worked on “trading” his treasure for a high value cookie, and that works. I throw the cookie away from the item, then pick item up out of his sight. 

He needs an understanding home who won’t push the boundaries that he is comfortable with. That being said, he is a wonderful companion who would be a great couch and hiking buddy (not interacting with other dogs, however).
He does not appreciate other dogs in his space - although he is a fine gentleman in his kennel room, with guests across from him.

He prefers patient soft spoken female humans, or a gentle-man who is patient and calm.

Email harescue1@aol.com or haar13@aol.com for an application. 

The application can also be found at http://fs30.formsite.com/HAA…/AdoptionApplication/index.html

Buddy is the calmest and most laid-back dog ever!

When we got the call to pick him up he was protecting his girlfriend who was in heat - and he was pretty beat up from doing it..  He had wounds on his head, a big hole in his leg, and a badly torn foot pad.  After he came home from the vet he dutifully wore his plastic collar for weeks without a word or tearing it off.  He never complained and never had any accidents in the crate.

  He is so patient and good natured, yet loves to run and play with a favorite girl of similar size as he doesn't realize his own strength.  A home with a female dog would be heaven for him.

He loves the car (and hates to have to get out of it after a ride) and walks well on a leash.  

He needs a fenced yard and someone with the time and love to give him - you will be richly rewarded with a great dog as a companion..  If you think you fit the bill, please call (landline only - no texts) me at 575-586-0784.

Breed: American Staffordshire Terrier X
DOB: 6/2013
Gender: male
Altered: yes
Coat: medium
Size: medium
Color(s): brown/white, streak of black on tail
Description:

***Needs a Foster Home***
This dog is in need of a foster home as well as a permanent home. If you are interested in fostering please fill out an online application.

Hi, I'm Jackson a sweet American Staffordshire Terrier X who was rescued from an LA shelter by someone out-of-state who wanted to give me a chance at finding my forever home.

I was evaluated by a trainer who said I was stressed but calm. Who wouldn't be stressed not knowing when your last day might be.

I accepted being touched all over my body including my paws, tail and mouth. I know sit, shake and take treats gently. I did not exhibit any food aggression when tested with chicken.

The trainer took me for a 30 minute walk and I pulled at first but listened to instructions about not pulling. I walked well after that. I did not react to strangers or other dogs we encountered on our walk. I showed more interest in people. This has since changed while I was in a foster home. I need to be the only dog in the home. I jumped in the trainer's car when given water after our walk. I didn't want to get out, I thought I was going home.

I'm grateful and happy to be in a safe place where I'll be taken care of and given lots of love and attention. I hope the next car I jump into will take me to my forever home.

Someone who hasn't even met me in person was willing to give me a chance, won't you give me a chance too? Stop by and meet me. I'll be waiting.

*Thank you to Jill for sponsoring this wonderful dog at the Burnice Kraemer Sanctuary and giving him the chance for a better life.

Additional information: *Current on shots

Argamo is located in Huntington NY . He is a little bit unsure about other dogs , a meet and greet is required . He is not a fan of cats .

To become his new family please apply today by filling in the  adoption link to find on our website www.a-teameliterescuedogs.com or email us and we send you one

animal.description: Casey is a 9 year old neutered male sable & white Sheltie. He came from a bad situation and is shy with people until he gets to know you. He has come a long way from the fearful dog he was through a lot of socialization in his dedicated foster home. He has settled in nicely to family life and seems very happy to be around people. He has become accustomed to most noises that once scared him, but he still panics at some particularly loud noises such as thunder and power tools.  He is more comfortable around women than men and still is somewhat fearful with men. His foster family is working with him everyday to continue to build his trust with men. Casey is crate trained, but he prefers to hang out in a comfy corner of the kitchen. Casey would do well with a female owner that could spend lots of time with him. He is very loving and is a good companion. Casey has been diagnosed with dry eye and will need inexpensive eye medication administered daily for life. He also has some elevated kidney values and must be kept on another inexpensive medication for this, on food with less than 30% protein content, and monitored by a vet every 6-12 months going forward. Casey also had a tumor removed from his leg and our vet was able to get great margins and does not expect a recurrence. Casey has been through a lot and is very deserving of a loving adoptive home. If you're interested in meeting or adopting Casey, please fill out an application via our website scsheltierescue.com. Casey is house trained and crate trained. Fenced yard and experience with Shelties is required. Casey's adoption donation of $250 includes neuter, dental cleaning, microchip and vaccinations. FEBRUARY 2021

animal.description: Bossco is a happy, energetic young dog. He loves people and is always happy to see you. He is very smart and loves learning new things. Bossco is an enthusiastic about life in general but he gets especially excited to do nose work, a fun search and scenting sport. Since coming to the Sanctuary, Bossco has become an expert at it. Born in 2017, Bossco has some respiratory issues that limit his ability to go for walks with the leash clipped to a collar or certain harnesses, but he is currently trying a new harness that seems to help. He loves to run around in open spaces, do agility and get attention. Bossco gets very jumpy and mouthy when he gets excited, and he can jump fences. He's working on being calm for leashing, not jumping on people and staying calm while getting attention. When it comes to attention, Bossco will want to be the center of it in a home of his own. He would do best as an only pet so you can give him all your love. He will give you all his love in return.

animal.description:
Aspen is a sweet intelligent guy with some allergies that are controlled simply by diet. Aspen was adopted in 12/17 and returned 3/19 for a behavior change. Once back with us I reviewed all of his veterinary records from while he was in the home, the reasons he was seen and the multitude of times the family had boarded him in the short period he was with them. That explained a lot
to me about this "behavior change". We put him on a special diet for allergies and have provided a stable environment for him, Aspen has been nothing but wonderful here just as he was in his foster home prior to the adoption in 12/17. He's a great dog, comical, loves to play, loves water and needs a "forever" home with out children, female canine companion only.

We require that you have a fenced in yard, not a "kennel" in the yard AND we do not approve underground fencing. Depending upon the dog some exceptions are made for those who live in apartments. We also require that the adoptee will be a part of the family "living" within the home. Our adoption process may be found on our website at www.bitofheaven.org

Visits are scheduled by appointment only via emailing request to ownedbycaninesandlovit@yahoo.com

animal.description:
Adoption info can be found here in the last paragraph of this pet's profile or by visiting this direct link:   https://www.dfwpuppatrol.com/info/adoption

Miss Sadie is estimated to have been born in about Jan, 2014, weighs approximately 66 lbs, and is a Pitbull Terrier mix.  Sadie is a huge cuddle bug who loves to be next to her humans. She will definitely try those puppy dog eyes on you to let her get on the couch. She also loves to sunbathe whenever she gets the chance.  She can be a bit of a digger, so you have to watch her when she's outside alone for too long or you may end up with a big hole in your back yard. She loves her walks and is very great on leash. She knows basic obedience commands, has passed an obedience class with flying colors, and even knows a few special tricks. She is very excitable when humans come to visit as she loves everyone.  She likes tough toys and bones to chew on, but isn't great at playing ball.  She does have a bit of storm anxiety, but we don't coddle her during those storms and she does ok.  Sadie is housetrained and she is also crate trained, although it's not her favorite place to be.  She can be left out in the house for a few hours; however, she has occasionally been known to chew on a sock on the ground or a hat left out or anything plastic.  Sadie will do best and will be happiest with a family where she is the only pet and gets all the attention.  She deserves nothing less after all she's been through!

If you are interested in adding this pup to your family, please click here (or copy and paste https://www.dfwpuppatrol.com/info/adoption into your browser) to view our adoption info and where you will find the link to fill out our online Pre-Adoption Application.  Any questions can be directed to us at info@dfwpuppatrol.com.  All of our adoptable pups have a minimum requested adoption fee of $250 + tax    (pups 6 months and older) and $350    + tax   (pups under 6 months old), regardless of our expenses, and it includes vaccinations, spay/neuter, heartworm test for pups 8 months and older, heartworm treatment if tested positive, deworming and/or fecal test, parasite treatment if tested positive, microchipping, any immediate known health issues, and pups 4 months and older are kept current on monthly heartworm prevention.

animal.description:
Dannie's previous life was an unhappy one. She was left outside often longing to be near people and she began to get out of her backyard.  She was found roaming the neighborhood when our volunteer found her.  Her owners did not care to take her back and it was very obvious she didn't want to go back to her own home. She only wanted to stay with her finder as if she knew she would finally get some love and attention. Unfortunately Dannie tested positive for heartworm disease due to her neglected care but luckily for her our rescue was able to get her the treatment  she needed to make her healthy again. Dannie can be a apprehensive of some strangers but will warm up if you go slow with her.  She would be fine as an only dog or with a furry friend.  We don't know how she would be with kids but older respectful ones should be ok and a calmer home best. She likes attention and would be a good companion for someone able to devote the time and attention to her. She is approximately 7-8 years old  and deserves to enjoy the rest of her life being happy and loved.
A visible fence is required.http://homefurever.com/online-application/

animal.description:
Sugar
SAPA-A-45902
Female
Good with Dogs
Not good with cats
Unknown with children

We believe Sugar is about 2-3 yrs and she was a mother to 6 very healthy pups that have already found their forever home, it's now their mama's turn to find her "furever" home.

Sugar is incredibly sweet and fun to have. She loves to hunt for flies in the house or in the backyard and is pretty good at catching them. Stuffed squeaky toy are her weakness and the toys tremble with fear when she is around because she will find their center and rip is out. She is kennel trained and it is recommended that she continues to be in a kennel or locked into a room/ bathroom when you aren't home. She isn't destructive but she does like to climb onto things, such as counters, tables, and if she can she might try to climb higher onto pantries or refrigerators if she can. Aside from being a toy murderer she is very sweet and has alot of energy, so she would be a great running partner. If you have a hyper dog or puppy and would like to get them a playmate, Sugar would be a great dog to have because she is very good with playful dogs. She is not good with cats, however, because she like to chase and nip them and could potentially hurt them. Sugar is very cute; however, she can ONLY go home with an experienced dog owner. She is going to have to gain the trust of her future owner which can take time but believe me when I say it is worth it.

I am living in a San Antonio Pets Alive! foster home. By adopting me, you not only give me a new leash on life; you also save the life of an additional pet who can be rescued from euthanasia and placed in foster care. If you are interested in adopting me, please email adopt@sanantoniopetsalive.org with my name and ID#. Please allow up to 24 hours to respond, as all fosters work on a volunteer basis. To find out how you can get involved and help turn San Antonio into a no-kill city, please visit www.sanantoniopetsalive.org

animal.description:
My name is Blue-or Miss Blue. I am a sweet little girl who was 2 in April, 2020.  I have one brown eye and one blue eye, which is called heteroschromea 

I am current on all of my vaccines and also have a microchip and am spayed.  Am also on Heartworm meds and I am negative for HW and for tick diseases. I am  house trained and good in my crate and also in a crate in the car. I can ride for miles and miles and never make a peep. I hate being on a leash .I am reactive to seeing other dogs out in public. 

When I came into rescue it was noticed my one back leg looked different. Exrays showed that the ball that fits into the hp socked had been badly broken. The vet fixed me up with a surgery called a Femoral Head Ostomy-FHO. I am not pain free and can run like the wind.

I like to play with other dogs that I know and am very, very  energetic.  I play rough and due to the herding breed will go after back legs so another dog must be able to be large enough to be able to deal with that. She can put a 90 pound dog down to the ground by grabbing back legs and has no fear doing it.

Because I was a stray and am a High flight risk I will REQUIRE a secure physical wooden fenced yard where I can run and play safely. Fence must be at least 5 feet high .The house must have an entrance right into the fenced yard 

.   """Please don't apply if you don't have the fence that is required"""

I like to play outside with treat toys. I roll the toy around and the treats come out for me to snack on. 

I have a Heeler habit of wanting to herd , so older kids will be a better match. Only because she likes to grab back of ankles while herding. she has got so much better at that with adults though since she came into rescue.Small kids when running will trigger the herding instincts. She is a fun little girl. I would love to have people come and visit me as I love people. Due to the Covid that has been hard to do so will need more of the socializing when this situation gets better.

No long distance adoptions. 

If I might be the girl for you,contact  sue@crrow.org for more info  or an application. .



NOTE: DUE TO THE PANDEMIC THERE ARE NO MEETS UNTIL WE DEEM IT SAFE FOR FOSTER HOMES.

Hi, my name is Titan! Here is what would work best for me in my new home:

-Personality: Goofy, playful, happy-go-lucky, slobber-monster
-Can Live with Kids: Titan would do best with older, sturdy, dog-savvy kids aged 8+, given the knowledge that he WILL knock small ones over!
-Can Live with Cats: No, Titan has a very high prey drive.
-Can Live with Dogs: No, Titan prefers to be an only child.
-Can do Apartment Living: No-- this large, active boy needs room to run!
-Potty Trained: Yes
-Bite History: No
-Positive Reward Based Obedience Classes Required: Yes, at least one private lesson.
-Leash Trained: Yes, but is strong and can pull!
-Energy Level: High
-Needs Medical Procedure Before Going Home: No
-Additional Information: This large and in charge boy is TITAN and he's on the lookout for a forever family to love! Titan is a silly pup who LOVES to play. He's a big, loving meatball who definitely considers himself a lap dog. Titan has a flea allergy and will need regular flea treatments to keep him looking and feeling his best. If you're looking for a lifetime of love, laughter, and slobber, Titan just might be your boy!

animal.description:
Mookie & Victory are a bonded pair

Video: https://www.facebook.com/watch/?v=292784035174568 

Victory was only 10 weeks old in July 2019 when she was run over by a car and left on the side of the road. After two major initial surgeries, she went to the same foster home as Mookie. Even though he was only 5 months at the time, his gentleness and care for Victory melted our hearts. Victory had to undergo two additional surgeries. Mookie has been right by her side through all of her recoveries. They have a sweetness for each other that we just can’t separate, and we are adoptiong these two precious puppies as a bonded pair, together. Mookie is a total cuddler and loves to sleep next to his people in bed. He will curl up by you on the couch after a busy day of playing ball and chewing on his bones. He’s a confident, active, energetic pup with the most soulful puppy eyes you ever did see. Victory is also a love bug, with plenty of kisses to give. She’s a sweet, happy girl who wants to please her people. She's a complete darling, and everyone seems to just fall in love with her. Victory has been diagnosed with fibrotic myopathy which is a rare, idiopathic disorder. We officially consider Mookie her emotional support animal! If you’re interested in opening your heart and home to this pair of wonderful pups, we’ll be happy to talk to you further about Victory’s special needs.

Email gsdresq@gmail.com with your completed Adoption Application: http://tinyurl.com/gsrapp

More Photos:  https://tinyurl.com/y5u44q4w

Website:      http://www.goodshepherdrescuetexas.com/
Facebook:   https://www.facebook.com/GoodShepherdRescue
Application:  http://www.goodshepherdrescuetexas.com/#!adoption-application/cihc

PLEASE NOTE:  We do not respond to Petfinder inquiries with any information about the dogs.  Only pre-approved adopters are setup for meet & greets.  You must submit an application to start the approval process.  A volunteer will be in touch with you to discuss.  ALL dogs in our program are spayed / neutered, fully vaccinated, dewormed, microchipped, tested for heartworms & treated for heartworms if necessary.

---------------------------------------------------------
400.00 - Purebred Puppy
350.00 - Purebred Adult

animal.description:
Darling Hartley aka “greatest dog in the world” per his temp foster dad is still in need of a long term foster or forever home! He is 60lbs, 5/6yrs old, neutered and is so cute it’s ridiculous. He is mostly husky with a itty, bitty bit of asian breed. 

•

Hartley is a boy of simple pleasures and he has the time of his life. He gets to go to the park, the beach, and friends’ houses where he gets loved on by so many people. He may need a little extra care due to his medical needs (insulin & food every 12hrs, thyroid pill) but because of his easy going nature - so many other things are easy. He is a good boy about his insulin shots, in the car, at vet, in new environments, loves all humans including kiddos, and even tolerates nail clips and baths! More than getting along with other doggos, Hartley needs canine companionship to know he’s not alone as he does have isolation anxiety (fear of being alone). He is sight impaired and having another doggo simply helps reassure him. 

•

Hartley is so special because he loves so hard it’s impossible not to fall for him. He has all the reason to be slow to trust but he is so endearing! He will whine for attention because he’s figured out it’s so cute that most people can’t help but to give in. However, he does mellow out once ignored. We can’t blame him for trying!  He is of gentle, calm energy but can be playful, too once he’s settled in. 
?

?•
?
To adopt Hartley: please visit our website to complete an adoption application: www.twodogfarms.com/adopt
•
For foster: www.twodogfarms.com/foster
•

animal.description:
Charlie is a 7/8 year old Silky Terrier. He is generally a happy and loving pup, but he recently has been becoming protective of his home. He gets along with other dogs for the most part, but should be supervised with with other dogs.
He is a nervous dog, and needs people to go slow with him. Once he trusts you he'll follow you around everywhere, but it takes some patience and work to get to that point.
He needs an experienced adopter, with a calm household. He does best in a single person home, but can be in an all female or all male household (no female/male household). Also, no kids for Charlie!

He has recently started to have bouts of aggression when people enter the home, and has been seeing a behaviorist about it. He is fine with people in public.

Charlie walks great on a leash, though has occasional leash aggression, and is very treat motivated. His trainer has had success with him though positive reinforcement training.
He has a collapsed trachea and he coughs when hes being active. He also has dry eye, so he gets eye drops.

animal.description: This is Houch (HWTH#19063A). He is a Pit mix, DOB: 3/6/17. Houch weighs approximately 50 pounds and stands 18 inches at the shoulders. Houch was found by a Halfway to Home volunteer running the streets of the Antelope Valley. The volunteer took Houch to the local animal shelter where he stayed for 2 weeks without being claimed by his owner. At the end of the 2 weeks, the volunteer went back to the animal shelter and got Houch released. He then relinquished Houch to Halfway to Home. Houch is a very friendly boy who is high-energy and strong. He loves attention and gives small kisses. It will be imperative for Houch to have a kind, active owner willing to give Houch the love, good-quality human companionship, structure and playtime he deserves as well as the amount of exercise he needs to control his rambunctious nature in a positive way. He might make a good canine running partner for the right person or perhaps having another active canine to play with would help him release his energy in a positive way. When Houch is thoroughly settled in his new Forever home, he will benefit from positive basic obedience training to help with leash training and other obedience commands as well as the bonding process. With lots of love and the right amount of exercise, Houch will make a wonderful and very loving and loyal canine companion. He is good with other dogs but probably should be introduced slowly due to his rambunctious nature. He is crate friendly. animal.description:
Pony, female, mastiff mix. 10months old. 70lbs Dogs. Kids.


For starters we really want Pony to have a playmate in other dogs. It’s extremely important to her. She loves them and secondly she’s a little insecure innately and dog friends help her feel secure. Pony has energy to burn. Especially with being a larger breed mix when not socialized properly dogs change and then people run into problems down the road and want to give up. We see this commonly with puppies specifically. Her current life is filled with socialization, adventures and a house of solid dog friends. We also have to make sure you’re aware that she was born with not a fully closed skull. In affect, she has a knob on her head. We had an MRI and it showed that her brain is fully where it should be so that’s safe. The knob is filled with meningeal fluid which protects the brain. The specialist gave her an A+ on everything neurological and cognitive. He did recommend surgery but that is what surgeons do. Our vet thinks she could live a long prosperous life without surgery. Think of it as a third eye where you don’t want a stick going straight into (obviously). We choose to not do it. We recently did an elective surgery and almost killed the dog. That’s enough of that. She’s a happy, outgoing and extremely playful girl that has no idea what her size is. She’s never been crated and she’s fully potty trained and not destructive. She does spook more easily than not but anything aggressive doesn’t exist in her even remotely. shes extremely sensitive and we think magical. We know our dogs extremely well. We are full disclosure on every detail. We look for organic connections and humans willing to put in the work in. 

Animals can be viewed by appointment only. We ask that you review our adoption information AND fill out an adoption application prior to setting an appointment so we have all your information and you understand our adoption procedures - you can do so online here.     

Please feel free to email us or call us anytime for additional information on any of our animals - info@mcprescue.org or 312-388-3928. Our typical adoption fee varies based on the age of the dog at the time of rescue: Under the age of 1 years old is $500; 1-5 years old is $400; over the age of 5 is $300. Fees include vaccinations, microchip, deworming and other vetting as needed. Our adoption process includes an application, reference check and home visit.

animal.description:
(All notes supplied by Jack's current owner - we are listing Jack as a courtesy to him. If you are interested to find out more, please contact Brian directly at bktakagi@live.com)

Jack is 6 yrs, 3 months approx. old, 67lb
Located in Edmonds, WA, 98020

Neutered

Rabies 2019

no monthly worm/flea/tick treatments

Jack has epilepsy.  Takes Zonisamide, 100mg capsules: 2 orally morning, 2 orally evening (12 hr) with peanut butter.  Jack has a low threshold for seizure, meaning missing several doses will result in major tonic-clonic seizures.  They are terrible to witness.  Zonisamide runs 50 cents/pill, so $2.00/day, $60/month, $720/year.  Phenobarbitol is cheaper, but Jack has only taken Zonisamide since being diagnosed in March, 2017.  He had two seizures (03/2017, 06/2017) before treatment started, and has had three breakthrough seizures (the first breakthrough was during trial treatment- dose was doubled to current dose; the next two seizures occurred after I missed several doses).  He has not had a seizure since March, 2018. 

Jack has a very, very high prey drive, in addition to fear/anxiety of strangers.  He will most definitely be aggressive towards dogs, even if he is riding in the car and sees a dog on the street.  He has ripped the door paneling completely off the passenger door with one bite when he gets triggered.  He appears friendly/interested in strangers, wagging his tail but will most definitely give warning bite to the hand of anyone who gets close- ie, within 3-5 feet.  EXTREME CAUTION with strangers!  NO ONE should be allowed within 6-8 feet if new to Jack.  ABSOLUTELY NO CHILDREN anywhere near this dog- he can lunge so quickly and powerfully when he is inclined.  NO EXCEPTIONS.   If he knows the person, he is affectionate .

Jack is used to early morning (between 5am to 7am) walks.  Morning walk M-F 40-50 minutes, with hills, suburban and park environments.  AVOID other dogs, people running/cycling- he lunges at moving people/animals- dogs, birds, rabbits, squirrels.  He lunges at slow moving cars.  20-30 minute lunch walk suburban/park.  Weekend winters one day at cross country ski trails that allow dogs 1-2 1/2 hours on trail.  Summer weekend walks 50-80 minute walks, beach walk with super low tide (at hours with minimal people).  Trail  hikes are risky if trail is narrow as little room to pull dog off to make way for other hikers/dogs.  Jack is much better with pinch collar and water spray bottle.

Jack  spends most of his day indoors, but has a wooden deck at home to lounge outside for hours in spring, summer.  Jack is rarely left alone, as he is accustomed to staying at my office M-F- behind a gate.  On sunny days, he can lounge outside  on leash attached to side door. He gets regular attention and treats from employees. 

Walking Jack is a challenge.  Much less pulling/lunging with pinch collar over last three months.  Very reactive to other dogs and any animal/insect/moving thing.  Many oppose use of pinch collar, but for control purposes, it is currently effective.  Eventually, some other collar will be fine.  He is extremely wary of guard muzzle, but must be in muzzle in public as of May, 2019.  This aversion is why I'm looking to place Jack in new home. 

Jack is very sensitive and has numerous no-go zones: tail- beautiful and curled and fluffy and don't play with it; lower tummy by genitals- he's very private;  does not like behind getting wiped when he has soft/wet stool on long coat.  Don't try to pick him up- he will aggressively resist.  He does not enjoy bathing, does enjoy his teeth getting brushed (Petrodex with red label).

Jack rides in the car seven days per week.  For Vet visits, he needs multiple meds for sedation- mainly to get muzzle on.  If not sedated, Jack is aggressive in the waiting room if other dogs are present (they always are).  He is very nervous in the exam room.  He has taken Trazadone and Gabapentin and gets mildy sedated, but not enough for muzzling.  Valium, Trazadone, and Acepromazine allowed muzzling.  Needs four hours for effective sedation (Vet claims two hours, but I have not seen that work for this dog).  He will forcefully resist examination even when sedated.  Muzzle must be on very tightly.

After five years of ownership, on May 1, 2019, Jack bit a woman on the leg that needed stitches.  In the eyes of the woman, and the Animal Control office (the local police department), it was deemed "unprovoked", and Jack was legally declared a "dangerous dog" by WA state law.  This declaration is under appeal (court date 06/05/2019), but regardless, a second bite (of person or domestic animal), is a automatic class C felony for me and euthanasia for Jack.
I have not seen Jack act out at home by being left alone, as he is not left longer than eight hours but a handful of day per year.  If I'm out of town, I pay an employee to stay at my house so his routine and diet are uninterrupted.

Due to the harsh legal consequence of a second bite offense, I am looking to place Jack in a new home that can manage a loyal, loving dog who has aggressive tendencies.

animal.description:
Meet Chad!

ATTENTION: PLEASE READ THROUGH TO SEE WHETHER YOU MEET OUR ADOPTION CRITERIA BEFORE RESPONDING. IF YOU MEET OUR CRITERIA FOR ADOPTION OF THIS DOG, PLEASE FOLLOW THE LINK TOWARD THE BOTTOM OF THE PROFILE TO COMPLETE OUR APPLICATION. THANK YOU!

Chad is an adorable two-ish year old Pit bull mix (we think), possibly with some kind of Spaniel? His spots are SO CUTE! He is exactly as you'd imagine a 45lb puppy would be, active, happy, and needy. Hahaha. Chad is insecure and guarded with new people, but once he knows someone he is very snuggly. He is impossibly soft and loves to give kisses. 

This boy is very playful and loves other dogs - but he has no social graces. So he’s not a dog park kind of pup, instead he would love carefully selected and managed play dates in his backyard. He does have some jealousy/guarding issues with other dogs in his home so he should be an only pet, apart from play dates with good furry friends, of course. 

Chad is very sensitive and needs an experienced owner who can model confidence for him, and be the strong leader and protector that he needs. Like any dog, Chad would benefit from training. He is very treat motivated and loves to learn so training will just take a commitment on the part of his people. 

Chad will need at least two walks a day and really needs someone who is home a lot of the day. He wants to live in a house (not an apartment) with a securely fenced yard. While Chad loves kids, he doesn’t understand that little people are delicate, so he’d do best with older kids only. This poor pup also doesn’t realize that cats and other small pets are delicate too, so he can’t live with them either. 

Adoption Process: We are not first come first served. Indigo Rescue focuses on finding good matches between dogs and families to ensure life long adoptions. We deliver all dogs to their new homes. All of our dogs are in foster homes. 

If you’re interested in meeting one of our dogs, please use the following link and complete our Adoption Application. You can either scan your completed application and email it to us at: info@indigorescue.org, or you can fax it to us at: 888-502-7660.
The link is not live, so you will need to copy and paste it into your browser: https://storage.googleapis.com/gator-users/user-680788/documents/d1742bff02e44c2ea25649cb45df5103/Pet%20Application%20Form%20December%202020.pdf

If the dog you're interested in seems compatible with your lifestyle we'll set up a time for you to meet the dog privately.

animal.description:
Meet Hector!

Hector was seen for months at a flood control center here in Houston. The workers would feed him, and finally we were contacted to take him in so he is off the streets. Most workers were nice to him, but some bragged to us about stomping their feet and yelling at him to chase him away. We were upset to hear this, Hector is such a gentle soul. We were able to rescue him and gain his trust. 

We are not at all sure what his breed mix is, but he has an easy going and goofy temperament once he get comfortable with people. He is initially shy with going to new places, he does take a few days to adjust to a new environment (which is understandable from what he has been through). He loves peanut butter and belly rubs. He would be best as the only animal in the house as he has not gotten comfortable around other animals yet. Hector thinks he is a lap dog, so be warned about the cuddles he will want!

Hector is 79 lbs, 4 years old, neutered, up to vaccinations, microchipped, and heartworm negative!

Adoption or foster applications can be found at www.adorehouston.org

Email us at info@adorehouston.org with any further questions.

I don't bark much anymore and I also got used to people coming and going and I love it when they play ball with me. I have always been the only dog in my home so not sure about being around too many of them at a time and not sure I want to be friends with them, but I might. I am really hoping to get my own home and family soon.

I would do best in a home with no cats or young children.  His foster parents feel  Bowser needs dog savvy owner who will give him lots of walks and attention.  He is smaller and very handsome in person.

If you are interested in adopting Bowser, please complete the online application for adoption at Before the Bridge Senior K9 Rescue at www.beforethebridge.ca

animal.description:
"Happy" is the perfect name for this smiling, streamlined, young guy! His affectionate nature will have you smiling, too, we promise!
We believe him to be a Carolina Dog (American Dingo)/Mix. Carolina Dogs can still be found living in the wild in parts of the Southern US, but they've also become beloved pets to many happy dog owners. Please look up this breed.

Happy is reserved at first, but quickly forms a strong bond with humans and is loyal. He is pack oriented and loves to be by your side, regardless if you are outside doing  yard work or lying at your feet while watching TV. He is housebroken and follows willingly and easily rules inside the house. He is intelligent, very trainable and so eager to please and happily and enthusiastically follows directions.. He loves and needs rules and boundaries. 

Happy is a young guy, his DOB is 05/15/2018, and has energy to spare.  He would do best as an only dog.
While in foster, he was doing well around a dog-savvy cat. Happy is unsure of children and would do best with teenagers and adults. Happy does have prey-drive and we think he would do best in a home without small pets and livestock.

Happy is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, tested negative for heartworm and is on heartworm prevention. He weighs 57 lbs. All our animals must be indoor pets. Dogs are very social animals; there's really no such thing as a "good outdoor dog".

If you would like to meet Happy please schedule an appointment, and if Happy  would be the second dog in your family, give us a call and schedule a Meet and Greet under supervision at our shelter with your spayed or neutered dog. 830-980-2247 or BAHShelter@yahoo.com.

Due to COVID-19 the shelter is only open for scheduled appointments at this time.

animal.description:
RayRay is a charming fellow that spews happiness and rainbows due to his positive and delightful disposition. Never meeting a stranger, RayRay loves EVERYONE. When he meets dogs he's instantly passing out kisses and wagging his tail. That goes for humans, as well! He's even fine with cats as long as they are gentle with him. He's also been known to smother kids in kisses. :)

RayRay was treated for heartworms but is doing well. He's now put on weight, is crate trained, and is about 90% potty trained. He does require an inexpensive supplement for his allergies and has done extremely well since starting this - no more itching!

RayRay appears to be a victim of a Traumatic Brain Injury...but don't be alarmed! He is completely unfazed by this diagnosis, as life is a bowl full of jelly beans and sunshine to RayRay! He's a very intelligent guy, albeit slightly clueless, and he's happy to please his family. He has a little trouble with depth perception (e.g. he's slower going down steps), but it's not life altering for him. He runs around the yard, plays with his toys and his friends, and lives life like any other dog. There is no treatment for TBI, and he has a perfectly fine prognosis, so there's no need to think he's a tough medical case to handle...he just spins to the left sometimes, wears a perma-grin, and sometimes needs you to lead him in the right direction...but he's very independent and handles himself well. He's not a dog that needs constant assistance. He lives a very happy and positive life with many, many years ahead of him to brighten everyone's day. Allow him to pick his favorite spot to sleep on a nice cozy doggy bed, and he's good to go. 

RayRay need someone that is understanding of his need for guidance with potty habits. While he knows he's supposed to go outside, he hasn't quite mastered how to tell you. You'll find him spinning and rather anxious when he needs to go potty, desperately trying to relay the message, but if you're not around he doesn't know how to find you to let you know. As a result, he does have to be understood in this regard. He's super in a crate, but he can't be left in the crate more than a few hours b/c if he gets excited it prompts him to go to the bathroom, leaving a mess. So if gone for an extended amount of time, he goes to doggy daycare...which he LOVES!!! He is a staff favorite at doggy daycare and is thrilled when he realizes he's there, jumping out of the car and dashing to the door!

With patience on training, RayRay might benefit quite well from a doggy door. Just remember that he'd need to be able to go into a securely fenced yard. Another dog would be a great support system for him with this, both as a teacher and an aide, and make him quite happy and secure since he loves dogs so very much.

Again, RayRay does need a fenced yard due to his special need. He also enjoys laying in she sunshine and relaxing. So since he can't be trusted off leash, and because it could be dangerous for him, he'll require that fence. RayRay does walk well on a leash, although sometimes he can spin to the left and sometimes walk a little slower in a new setting. He just needs to get a gist of where he's at and what's going on. However, he's always game for an adventure! He LOVES a car ride!

RayRay is a super special guy that knocks the socks off of all who are blessed to meet him. If you love that smile as much as we do, let us know! We'll be happy to fill you in on how you can have this 4 legged bundle of joy in your life.

animal.description:
Hank and Topaz are long term lovers looking for a home together. They are good with kids and other dogs both big and small, and are willing to travel anywhere to find their perfect home! Please share!! 

Hank and Topaz are both big lovable babies sitting at around 85 lbs each. They are incredibly well trained. You won't need to worry about these 2 chewing or destroying anything. They listen well and are very calm quiet pups.
They are kennel trained, house trained, and are healthy, fixed, and fully vaccinated. 

We found these guys in a very rural shelter that had plans to put all the dogs down before CHR came to the rescue. They were found on the streets together, were housed in the shelter together, and we plan on keeping them together- otherwise Hank cries and cries for his Topaz to come back. These 2 were very lucky to find a foster mom to care for them for a few months and nurse them back to health. When her time was up we had to put them in boarding where they remain today. 

These guys love their boarding facility where they get to play with other dogs and get treats all day long. After a long hot day playing in the pool, they get to cuddle each other all night. Although this sounds great, they can't stay there forever. And i know they would love a couch to lounge on and a family to come home to them every day. 

We've had them for 6 months now and we are dedicated to finding them the home that they've been waiting so long for. Please share this post far and wide!! 

Apply to foster or adopt at canehavenrescue.com 

Message us with any questions!! 
Located in New Orleans, Louisiana

animal.description:
Hi, everyone. My name is Luke. I’ve been at TIRR Rescue since 2018.

My dad was a soldier, and he had to leave the country to go save people. I’m a very particular dog when it comes to who I obey and who I don’t. My dad wasn’t sure anyone could handle me, so he brought me to TIRR Rescue, a place known for helping unruly dogs. Well, Dad wasn’t sure when he’d be back home, so he asked TIRR Rescue to find me a good home.

I select my dog friends very carefully. Right now, I only hang out with Boomer. I like to talk trash at the fence, but I’m sweet when you get me out. I like to be loved on a little, but I don’t like to be crowded, so I’d do best in a home without younger children. Also, I may be getting older, but I still like to run, so a running partner would be pretty nice!


PERSONALITY:
Luke is a cool dog who just needs a little time to warm up to people.  He likes to bark at the fence, but is sweet when he's around people.  He can be a little intense, so he'd do best in a home without children or cats.  He chooses his dog friends carefully, so a doggie introduction is a must for any potential adopters.

animal.description:
Hey, everyone!  My name is Boomer.  I came to TIRR Rescue from Oklahoma back in 2018.

I had an awesome family.  I was spoiled rotten, usually getting things my way.  Then we had a baby.  Don't get me wrong, I liked the baby.  I just didn't like certain people being around the baby.  One time, when my mom's mom was babysitting, we got into it with each other.  She was worried I was going to hurt the baby (which was dumb; I had issues with her, not the baby) and made my parents get rid of me.

They brought me to TIRR Rescue to find a new forever home.  I'm a pretty cool dog, but I don't like to feel cornered or trapped.  If you try to be pushy with me, I will snap at you.  I'm a great dog; I just need the right person to come along and adopt me!  If you think you might be that person, be sure to contact my rescue people!

~~~~

PERSONALITY:
Boomer is a sweet old dog with a bit of a grumpy side.  He doesn't like to be pushed around or feel trapped; he will bite if he feels threatened.  We believe he might have been cornered and hurt at one point and learned that if he exploded, he would be left alone.  He would do best in a home without young children.  He needs adopters who understand his boundaries.  He would do great with an older couple who let him curl up on the couch with them.
?
~~~~

To learn more about Boomer, please visit tirrrescue.org/boomer.

Meet handsome Ollie! Ollie is a five-year-old Blue Heeler mix, weighing in at 64 pounds. He's neutered and up-to-date on shots. animal.description:
Yoshi is a beautiful chow mix who has been with us for several months.  He came in as a mostly unsocialized boy who was scared to be touched by people and afraid to leave his run.  He has come a long way and now happily goes out in the dog park with our volunteers, plays with toys and loves his walks and treats.  But he can be unpredictable so we are not willing to adopt him to a family with children.  Yoshi's ideal family lives in a quiet home with a fenced yard, has no children, shows patience and is willing to train. 

Yoshi is a man who knows what he likes and what he doesn't. This floofy ChowChow mix has favorite toys that make him skip and hop like a fox! When he tips the scales into 'goofy' play, you'll find him rolling his face in the grass like it's the best chin scratch he's ever had in his life! 

Yoshi does not care for being touched or handled which makes finding the right home for him very difficult. Yoshi's family will need to commit to helping him overcome some of his fears by spending the weeks it will take to get to know him here at the shelter and continuing his muzzle and behavior modification training at home.  A Certified Professional Dog Trainer has committed to work alongside Yoshi's shelter family and a Certified Behaviorist to transition Yoshi into a family willing to take on this diamond in the ruff.

animal.description:
Charlie is a sweet and loving 8 year old boy. He is very social and loves to give kisses. Charlie is extremely obedient and lives with 6 other Bassets but can be territorial of his owner and space. He would be best in a home as an only dog. He is fine with cats and actually likes to play with them. Charlie loves to ride in cars, go for walks, is housebroken, sits for treats and loves his human. He loves sleeping on dog beds and will move it around to find the perfect napping spot.
Charlie is house and doggy door trained and loves going on walks.

Charlie does have a slightly twisted front right leg and some shoulder tension. Xrays do not show any kind of injury so perhaps a genetic issue. He is on joint supplements for aid and will need to stay on those to continue to help him.

If you have the perfect home for Charlie, please fill out an Adoption Application. http://suncoastbassetrescue.org/AdoptionForm.aspx

Tiny Alice is sweetness personified. This darling senior weighs only 7 pounds dripping wet. Her age is estimated at 10+ years. As soon as she is ready, we'll be removing her mammary tumors but for now she has a fresh mouth, a great appetite, and nice pep in her step. She was even doing a little old lady run in her foster home! She's an incredible old gal.

YOU CAN SPONSOR ALICE'S CARE IN RESCUE BY CLICKING ON THE SPONSOR BUTTON ON THIS PAGE or DIRECTLY ON THE RESCUE'S WEBSITE: www.onmywayhomerescue.com.  Thank you so very much for caring and supporting our rescue mission!  


You can apply to adopt or foster at http://www.onmywayhomerescue.com/how-to-adopt.html.    


Quick Dachshund Facts
Dachshunds are in the hound dog breed group.
They’re known for their short legs and long bodies.
Common nicknames are: doxies, dachsies, sausage dogs, wiener dogs, and hot dogs.
Pronunciation of the word “dachshund” is DAK-sund and not “dash hound.”
There are four sizes: toy dachshund (smallest), miniature dachshund, tweenie, and standard dachshund.
Their average weight is under 11 pounds (toy dachshunds and miniature dachshunds),  11 to 16 pounds (tweenies), and 16 to 32 pounds (standard dachshunds).
Their average life span is 12 to 15 years.
There are three varieties of dachshund fur: smooth or shorthaired; longhaired; and wire-haired.
They come in many colors and patterns.
They were bred to dig and they will dig holes in your yard if you let them.
They have a loud, deep bark that people will assume is coming from a large dog. That makes them great guard dogs!
They’re considered clever, intelligent, and mischievous.
Dachshunds are very affectionate. They often bond most with one person and can become clingy, in a cute way.
They’re stubborn and notoriously hard to housebreak. Vets and trainer recommend crating them on a schedule to solve this.
They’re not easy to train. It takes a lot of patience, and will include a lot of laughter.
They’re brave. They show it by barking and sometimes by lunging at other dogs.
When they’re puppies especially, they’ll chew up your shoes, book covers, and other objects.
Dachshunds are prone to becoming overweight. To keep your doxie healthy you’ll need to monitor his food intake carefully and take him on daily walks.
Dachshunds love to jump on high things. But they can also develop herniated or slipped disks because of jumping down. So you need to keep an eye on them and place them on the ground.
When you hold them, you need to give support to their backs with your hand.
You should only get a dachshund from responsible breeders and rescue organizations, which you can research in advance on the Internet.

animal.description:
DUE TO TIME CONSTRAINTS, MESSAGES ASKING QUESTIONS THAT ARE ANSWERED IN THE BIO WILL NOT RECEIVE A RESPONSE. ALL DOGS LISTED ARE AVAILABLE.

** Please read the bio in its entirety before emailing with questions or submitting an application **

Hey everyone! My name is Paco and I'm what foster mom calls a Chi-weenie (Chihuahua/Dachshund). I'm 4 years old and a little guy, approximately 10 lbs.

Foster mom says I'm super snuggly, whatever that means. I know I really like hanging out on the couch with her and I'll lay with my neck on her shoulder when given the chance. I don't like meeting new people because they scare me, but I become really attached to my one special person. For this reason, it's best I don't go out in public places because I may not be nice to the people I meet. I can be a little bit of a resource guarder when it comes to my foster mom, but she says it's easy to manage, so I'll take her word for it.

My legs may be little but I love being outside and running to my heart's content. They say I'm very special in one way though, I love other dogs, especially the big ones! My favorite dog in my foster home is a very sweet 55 lb Pit Bull. I adore her! I sometimes run underneath her if something scares me. While I don't like being picked up, I listen well.
I'm neutered, heartworm negative and up to date on vaccines. You can find an adoption application at www.pawprintsnky.com.

If you have specific needs that aren't addressed in the bio (children in the home, small animals, apartment/condo living, etc) please email to ask if the dog is suitable for the environment before submitting an application. Once the application is submitted, please expect someone to email you with questions and/or provide more information about the dog is we are unsure that the dog may be a good fit.

Most importantly, please be honest! We have many people tell us what they think we want to read, not what's truthful. If there are discrepancies, your application will be denied. It's important for us to place dogs in a home that's suitable. You may be a stellar owner but possibly not a good fit for the dog you were first interested in adopting. We're not trying to offend anyone, we're trying to set everyone up for success. We're a best fit rescue and will verify your vet and personal references.

*Chihuahua/Dachshund

*4 years old

*10 lbs

*Good with cats and dogs (including large dogs)

*Not recommended for a home with children or one where children visit

* Best in a single person home but may adjust to a home with two people

* No homes that share walls with neighbors

* Needs a fenced in yard as he does not do well on walks

*Adopters must live within 2 hours of Florence, KY

*Adoption fee is $200.00

animal.description:
**WE ONLY DO HOME VISITS FOR ADOPTIONS NEAR BROWARD & PALM BEACH COUNTIES**

PLEASE READ HIS FULL BIO BEFORE APPLYING TO ADOPT! Happy boy Harrison is eager to win your heart! Harrison was turned over to the police and was on his way to a kill facility if we didn't step up to save him. He has lower lumbar paralysis, meaning he can't use his rear legs. He is also bladder and bowel incontinent, so his bladder needs to be manually expressed 4 plus times a day. His bowel movement release on its own and you can manually speed the process most of the time. Harrison has no idea he is injured, he happily plays fetch and lives each day to the fullest. He is a wonderful companion for someone willing to keep up with his needs and in-home physical therapy. We are looking for that special person to see past his limitations and fall in love with his very deserving spirit. His previous people did get him the spinal surgery but didn't seem to do rehab. Hes been receiving Acupuncture, laser therapy, physical therapy and aqua therapy with a group of specialists who have trained us how to continue his therapy at home. He has also had I-Therm therapy which has helped and we are looking to get a machine for our rescue to continue his rehab and help our other special needs dogs. He shows signs of feeling from his paws and he has positive reactions to therapy. He sometimes uses his legs by showing strength. We are hopeful he will walk with continued home therapy. This absolutely adorable little guy is only two years old and 8 pounds. He has wheels that he can do his zoomies around the house and he travels well in the car, always ready to meet people. We are looking for a home for him who can keep up with his monthly grooming and heartworm prevention as well as daily health care and maintenance. His adoption fee is $200 to go towards his vetting (vaccines, spay/neuter, heartworm/Ehrlichia/Lyme test, fecal test, pre-op blood work, dental cleaning, microchip, and all his therapy/rehab). If you feel you can fulfill Harrison's needs he will drown you with kisses and his fantastic personality! Check his VIDEO PLAYLIST here. Please Like & Follow his FaceBook Page. If you are interested please fill out the adoption application For additional information regarding our adoption process, please check our FAQ's Page. WWW.GETALIFEPETRESCUE.COM

*All dogs in the care of Get a Life Pet Rescue live in loving foster homes while waiting for their perfect match. They don't live in cages or crates (unless there is a medical reason to do so.) They are treated as family pets while in our care. *All dogs in our care are fed premium brand holistic food as well as supplements and vitamins specific to each dog's needs. We don't buy inexpensive bulk dry kibble, our rescues are fed premium wet food diets as part of a comprehensive rehabilitation program to ensure maximum health. * All of our rescues receive complete quality vetting including full dental cleaning with pre-op bloodwork, spay/neuter, vaccines, and grooming. Dogs in need of specialized medicine will be seen by specialists, such as full cardiac workups, ophthalmologist visits, all suspicious lumps, and bumps are biopsied, and every medical need is transparent to potential adopters. *Once you adopt from Get a Life Pet Rescue, you become part of our compassionate family and we are here for you if a problem with your precious dog arises.

He's made significant improvements with all the training he's done at the sanctuary, but his new person or family will need to keep working with him. Fenced yard

My name is Roscoe and I have a sad story. You see, my dad died suddenly and I was there when it happened. animal.description:
Hello! My name is Toby. I have been at TIRR Rescue since 2017.

I came to TIRR Rescue from South Texas.  When I got here, I had an injury to my front, right paw.  The vet ended up having to amputate all but one toe on that paw.  I hardly even notice it now, though I don’t like to talk about it much.

I love attention and will give lots of affection once I get to know you. I love to play with large sticks, especially if someone throws them for me.  I am a bit of a fence guarder, meaning that I act real tough when someone I don't know comes too close to my fence or gate.

I will need a strong, confident leader who can help me when I get nervous and can handle me when I get too excited while playing and forget how big I am.  I would love to have a yard of my own with lots of trees so I have plenty of sticks to choose from, though going to the park often would be good, too.  If you think you might be my new forever family, be sure to contact my rescue people!

~~~~

PERSONALITY:
Toby is a good ol' boy and is very affectionate with people he knows.  He can play a little rough and doesn't like people in his face, so he'd do best in a home without small children.  He also has a slight foot fetish, so shoes are best worn when around him!

~~~~

To learn more about Toby, please visit tirrrescue.org/toby.

animal.description:
Hey, y'all! My name is Radar. I came to TIRR Rescue several years ago with my mom, back when I was teeny tiny.

Mom and I were found walking down the middle of the road near a school in Wise County. Mom was dragging a bike cable that she had chewed through to get free, and I was trying my darndest to keep up!

I got adopted once, went home, and went to obedience school and everything. However, they returned me because I scared my German Shepherd brother so badly, he didn't even want to come in the house. It wasn't my fault, though; he was acting up, so I whipped him good. I don't put up with bad behavior...ask Bo!

I’m a really sweet girl, though a little aloof to strangers. While I like people, I really prefer the company of other dogs. I sure would like to be adopted again. It felt nice being in a home with my very own yard. It would be even cooler if someone took both Bo and me home together!

If you think you might be my forever family, be sure to contact my rescue people!

~~~~

PERSONALITY:
Radar can be a bit aloof to strangers.  She tends to prefer the company of dogs but likes hanging out with her trusted humans, especially if she can spend some time chilling outside in the sun.  Radar is very obedient and loyal to her family.  If you win her trust, you will have a loyal companion who will have your back for life.

~~~~

To learn more about Radar, please visit tirrrescue.org/radar.

You see, my owner left me locked up in a crate in the Texas heat when he moved.  A nice lady found me and decided to help me.  She busted me out, cleaned me up, and took me home.  However, her dogs weren't too fond of me, so she brought me to TIRR Rescue, hoping they could help me find an awesome forever home.

I do well with other dogs, especially if they like to play and run.  When I go to my new forever home, it would be nice to have a playful and rambunctious sibling...or a super active family!

I love people - being around them, being loved on by them, and playing with them.  I never met a stranger, and I always love meeting new people!

animal.description:
Hey, guys!  My name is Murphy.  I came to TIRR Rescue in the summer of 2018.

I was adopted from TIRR Rescue twice before.  The first time, I got returned because the family didn't realize how high energy I would be.  They just couldn't quite keep up with me.  The second time I got adopted, I got protective of the kids and it kind of scared the parents.  It wasn't anyone's fault; I just wanted to make sure everyone who tried to get near my kids had good intentions.

Anyway, I'm now back at TIRR Rescue waiting for the perfect family; the family that can keep up with my active lifestyle while also understanding and controlling my protective instincts.  I would make a great running buddy or playmate.  While I play really well with kids, I could use a little bit of training, because I sometimes play a little too rough with adults.

I'm a really great guy who just needs a really great forever family!  If you think you could be that family, be sure to talk to my rescue people about meeting me!

~~~~

PERSONALITY:
Murphy is an awesome dog who just wants to have fun!  He is super energetic and will need a very active family.  He loves kids (the younger, the better; the younger they are, the more energy they have to play with him!), but he can also be very protective of them.  He will need a strong leader who will give him the training he needs to control his protective instinct.  It is important to remember that Murphy will bit anyone he thinks is a threat to his kids, even if those people are family members.

~~~~

To learn more about Murphy, please visit tirrrescue.org/murphy.

I was sitting in a shelter when a nice person sent a picture of me to TIRR Rescue. They thought I was pretty awesome looking, with my bright blue eyes and pointy ears. They picked me up and brought me to the ranch as soon as they could.

animal.description:
Through no fault of her own Jolene needs a new forever home.  The owner, a friend of DFW Collie Rescue, adopted Jolene from an animal shelter when she was around 4 months old and had been picked up as a stray, she is now around 2 years old.  She probably has cattle dog and terrier in her, but truly is a Heinz 57.

Jolene is a happy little dog weighing about 40 lbs.  She gets along with big and medium size dogs, but has not been around little dogs on a regular basis, but will do best as an only dog. She can show her terrier side at times. Jolene will not come in the house, but does sleep in a crate at night. She does not enjoy riding but enjoys running and exploring in the fields and pasture.  She has been around cows and equine and has no interest in them and does not chase them,

It is the owner's opinion that she was abused in some way in her young life since she does cower if a hand is raised or voice is raised in anger.  She has always been somewhat afraid of her owner but does well with females and needs a female owner.  She wants attention and likes to be petted; but she is a little shy with new people and has not been around children.

Jolene is spayed, current on shots, on heartworm preventive, and microchipped.  She does well with having her toenails clipped and having a bath. Jolene will be a great companion and will be happy following you around on the farm or ranch.   She will do best with a woman.

DFW Collie Rescue will be adopting Jolene for the owner.  Application and terms of adoption can be found at www.dfwcollierescue.org.The application and terms of adoption are geared toward collie, but are appilcable to any breed.  A home visit is required (virtual can be arranged) and references contacted after the application and terms of adoption are received..A small adoption fee is required.  Please let Jolene entertain you.  If further info is needed email dfwcollierescue@gmail.com or call or text 214-668-5794.
